\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Alan Ball, Jr.|Alan Ball]]||{{flagu|England}}||May 1984&nbsp;\u2013 January 1989||222||94||58||70||{{#expr:94/222 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]]||{{flagu|England}}||January 1989&nbsp;\u2013 January 1990||50||10||15||25||{{#expr:10/50 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Frank Burrows]]||{{flagu|Scotland}}||January 1990&nbsp;\u2013 March 1991||60||20||17||23||{{#expr:20/60 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Jim Smith (footballer, born 1940)|Jim Smith]]||{{flagu|England}}||June 1991&nbsp;\u2013 February 1995||199||81||54||64||{{#expr:81/199 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Terry Fenwick]]||{{flagu|England}}||August 1995&nbsp;\u2013 January 1998||131||43||29||59||{{#expr:43/131 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Alan Ball Jr.|Alan Ball]]||{{flagu|England}}||January 1998&nbsp;\u2013 December 1999||97||28||26||43||{{#expr:28/97 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tony Pulis]]||{{flagu|Wales}}||January 2000&nbsp;\u2013 October 2000||35||11||10||14||{{#expr:11/35 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Steve Claridge]]||{{flagu|England}}||October 2000&nbsp;\u2013 February 2001||23||5||10||8||{{#expr:5/23 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Graham Rix]]||{{flagu|England}}||February 2001&nbsp;\u2013 March 2002||56||16||17||23||{{#expr:16/56 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Harry Redknapp]]||{{flagu|England}}||March 2002&nbsp;\u2013 November 2004||116||54||26||36||{{#expr:54/116 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Velimir Zajec]]||{{flagu|Croatia}}||November 2004&nbsp;\u2013 April 2005||21||5||4||12||{{#expr:5/21 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Alain Perrin]]||{{flagu|France}}||April 2005&nbsp;\u2013 November 2005||21||4||6||11||{{#expr:4/21 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Harry Redknapp]]||{{flagu|England}}||December 2005&nbsp;\u2013 October 2008||128||54||29||45||{{#expr: 54/128 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tony Adams]]||{{flagu|England}}||October 2008&nbsp;\u2013 February 2009||22||4||7||11||{{#expr:4/22 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Paul Hart]]||{{flagu|England}}||February 2009&nbsp;\u2013 November 2009||30||9||6||15||{{#expr:9/30 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Avram Grant]]||{{flagu|Israel}}||November 2009&nbsp;\u2013 May 2010||33||10||7||16||{{#expr:10/33 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Steve Cotterill]]||{{flagu|England}}||June 2010&nbsp;\u2013 October 2011||61||18||17||26||{{#expr:18/61 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Michael Appleton]]||{{flagu|England}}||November 2011&nbsp;\u2013 November 2012||51||13||11||27||{{#expr:13/51 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Guy Whittingham]] ||{{flagu|England}}||November 2012&nbsp;\u2013 November 2013 ||51||11||15||25||{{#expr:11/51 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Richie Barker (footballer, born 1975)|Richie Barker]] ||{{flagu|England}}||December 2013&nbsp;\u2013 March 2014||20||4||8||8||{{#expr:4/20 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Andy Awford]] ||{{flagu|England}}||March 2014&nbsp;\u2013 April 2015 ||55||20||17||18||{{#expr:20/55 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Paul Cook (footballer)|Paul Cook]] ||{{flagu|England}}||May 2015&nbsp;\u2013 May 2017||107||52||27||28||{{#expr:52/107 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Kenny Jackett]]||{{flagu|Wales}}||June 2017&nbsp;\u2013 Present||165||87||33||45||{{#expr:87/165 * 100 round 2}}\n|}\n\n===Caretaker managers===\n:''Figures correct as of August 2018''\n:''Includes all competitive matches.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:10em\"|Name!!Nat!!Managerial Tenure!!P!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Ron Tindall]]||{{flagu|England}}||September 1974||2||0||0||2||{{#expr:0/2 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tony Barton (footballer)|Tony Barton]]||{{flagu|England}}||March 1991&nbsp;\u2013 May 1991||12||5||2||5||{{#expr:5/12 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Keith Waldon]]||{{flagu|England}}||January 1998&nbsp;\u2013 January 1998||3||0||0||3||{{#expr:0/3 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Bob McNab]]||{{flagu|England}}||December 1999&nbsp;\u2013 January 2000||5||0||2||3||{{#expr:0/5 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Joe Jordan]]||{{flag|Scotland}}||November 2005&nbsp;\u2013 December 2005||2||0||0||2||{{#expr:0/2 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Stuart Gray (footballer, born 1960)|Stuart Gray]]||{{flagu|England}}||October 2011&nbsp;\u2013 November 2011||6||3||1||2||{{#expr:1/2 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Andy Awford]]||{{flagu|England}}||November 2013&nbsp;\u2013 December 2013 ||3||0||2||1||{{#expr:0/3 * 100 round 2}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Gary Waddock]]||{{flagu|England}}||April 2015&nbsp;\u2013 2 May 2015||4||1||1||2||{{#expr:1/4 * 100 round 2}}\n|}\n\n==Ownership==\nPortsmouth Football Club has operated under five different parent company names in its history:\n* '''Portsmouth Football and Athletic Company Limited''' (5 April 1898 \u2013 27 July 1912)\n* '''Portsmouth Football Club Limited''' (27 July 1912 \u2013 May 1999)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://companycheck.co.uk/company/00123460/PORTSMOUTH-FOOTBALL-CLUB-LIMITED/companies-house-data |title=Portsmouth Football Club Limited |work=Company Check |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Portsmouth City Football Club Limited''' (12 May 1999 \u2013 25 May 2010)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://companycheck.co.uk/company/03747237/PORTSMOUTH-CITY-FOOTBALL-CLUB-LIMITED/companies-house-data |title=Portsmouth City Football Club Limited |work=Company Check |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> (initially as 'Overflint Limited' from 7 April 1999 \u2013 12 May 1999)\n* '''Portsmouth Football Club (2010) Limited''' (25 May 2010 \u2013 10 April 2013)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://companycheck.co.uk/company/07264768/PORTSMOUTH-FOOTBALL-CLUB-2010-LIMITED/companies-house-data |title=Portsmouth Football Club (2010) Limited |work=Company Check |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> (initially as 'PFC Realisations Limited' from 25 May 2010 \u2013 23 November 2010)\n* '''Portsmouth Community Football Club Limited''' (10 April 2013 \u2013 Present)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://companycheck.co.uk/company/07940335/PORTSMOUTH-COMMUNITY-FOOTBALL-CLUB-LIMITED/companies-house-data |title=Portsmouth Community Football Club Limited |work=Company Check |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> (initially as 'Portsmouth Supporters Trust (Operations) Limited' from 7 February 2012 \u2013 14 September 2012)\n\nThe current owner of Portsmouth Community Football Club Limited is [[The Tornante Company]], which purchased the club from the Portsmouth Supporters Trust (PST) on 3 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2017/august/tornante-company-complete-purchase-of-portsmouth-fc/ |title=Tornante Company Complete Purchase Of Portsmouth FC |work=Portsmouth F.C. |date=3 August 2017 |accessdate=18 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Club crest==\n[[File:City Flag of Portsmouth.svg|thumb|left|Official flag of the [[Portsmouth|City of Portsmouth]]]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC 80's logo.png|thumb|upright=0.5|right|1980\u20131989.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth_City_Coat_of_Arms.jpg|thumb|upright=0.5|right|1993-1997.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC 90's logo.png|thumb|upright=0.5|right|1997\u20132008.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC crest.svg|thumb|upright=0.5|right|2015\u20132018.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC logo.jpg|thumb|upright=0.5|right|2018-Present. Shirt crest.]]\n[[File:Portsmouth FC logo.svg|thumb|upright=0.5|right|2018-Present. Club & Merchandising crest.]]\n\nAlthough Portsmouth F.C. were formed in 1898, the club did not have a club crest until one was introduced for the 1913\u201314 season. This would be the second season since Portsmouth's 1912 reformation, and their wearing of blue shirts for a second successive season. Their first season with a crest in 1913\u201314 would also become the last season before World War I began in 1914.\n\nThe official Coat of Arms of the [[Portsmouth|City of Portsmouth]] contains an eight pointed gold star and crescent moon on a blue shield, Portsmouth's adoption of the [[star and crescent]] is said to have come from when [[King Richard I]] (1157\u20131189), who granted the city \"a crescent of gold on a shade of azure, with a blazing star of eight points\" which he had taken from the [[Byzantine Emperor]]'s standard of Governor [[Isaac Komnenos of Cyprus|Isaac Komnenos]], after capturing [[Cyprus]].\n\nThe first 1913 Portsmouth F.C. crest was based on official symbols belonging to the town council of Portsmouth, which featured a golden eight-pointed star and a golden crescent moon.  The football club's first crest featured a horizontally elongated white crescent moon beneath a white five pointed star, with both symbols positioned in the centre of a blue four pointed shield. Portsmouth town council bestowed the privileged use (but not ownership) of their moon and star motifs to Portsmouth F.C., albeit with some colour and design changes.<ref name=\"historicalkits.co.uk\"/>\n\nThroughout their history Portsmouth F.C. have tried different variations of the crest before reverting to the basic gold star and crescent. After World War II, Portsmouth began using an eight-pointed star to match that used by the city of Portsmouth.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> In the 1950s and 1960s, the traditional crest was emblazoned on the shirt in white rather than gold but this was due to white being a cheaper alternative to a more expensive gold coloured thread.\n\nBetween 1980 and 1989, Portsmouth scrapped the traditional crest and replaced it with an entirely new design. This crest showed a football in front of an [[anchor]] (representing the navy) and a [[sword]] (representing the army), with the whole design surrounded by an outer ring of ships rope. An alternative version included a circular version of the traditional star and crescent crest in place of the football.\n\nDuring 1989 and 1993, the rope and anchor crest was dropped replaced with a simpler eight pointed star and crescent moon on a long narrow shield. At the foot of the shield, a blue banner featured \"''Portsmouth Football Club''\" written within it in capital letters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm|title=Portsmouth - Historical Football Kits|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1993-1997, the 1989-93 long narrow shield design was replaced by an embroidered badge of the city of Portsmouth Coat of Arms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm|title=Portsmouth - Historical Football Kits|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://greatestkits.co.uk/products/1993-95-portsmouth-home-shirt-l|title=1993/95 Portsmouth Home Shirt (L)|website=Greatest Kits|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nThe 1993-97 city arms crest was replaced in 1997, with an eight pointed gold star and a golden crescent moon on a blue shield edged with a gold outer rim. At the foot of the shield, a gold ribbon with \"''Portsmouth F.C.''\" written in blue gothic lettering completed the new design.  This new crest coincided with the rebuilding and reopening of the new Fratton End and tjhe clubs centennial anniversary in the 1997\u201398 season\n\nIn 2007, an additional \"Since 1898\" was added to the 1997 crest ribbon underneath the shield in time for the 2007\u201308 season.\n\nOn 6 May 2008, a month after their 110th Anniversary, Portsmouth revealed a new crest with a very three dimensional look, the tradition curved shield with \"three points\" at the top of the shield were replaced with two straightened angles, with \"Portsmouth F.C.\" written above the star on the shield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ffcw001.azureedge.net/-/media/team/england/crest/portsmouth.png?w=600&h=600|title=Portsmouth Crest|last=|first=|date=|website=ffcw001.azureedge.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The traditional elongated crescent moon was replaced with a new circular one, which closely resembled that on the city's Coat of Arms. The new crest had its debut in the 2008 FA Cup Final, in which Portsmouth also wore a new 110th Anniversary all-blue commemorative home strip.\n\nAs part of the World War I Centennial Commemorations in the 2014\u201315 season, the club opted to replace the 2008 crest on the home kit with one almost identical to that used in 1913\u201314. This was a more traditional-looking club crest featuring the traditional three points at the top of a slightly rounded shield but with a silver five-pointed star inside instead of the usual eight-pointed one. The moon featured on the crest was also silver, both appearing on a blue background.\n\nIn June 2015, following positive feedback from supporters, Portsmouth F.C. decided to revert the official club crest back to a familiar and traditional design, over the one introduced in 2008, which was often criticised by Pompey fans for looking too similar to Arsenal F.C.'s updated modern era crest. Portsmouth's new 2015 crest was virtually identical in design to that which has been used for the majority of the club's history. The famous \"star and moon\", both silver-white on a blue background, have a slight three-dimensional appearance. The star was restored back to the familiar eight pointed design, instead of the five pointed version used in the 1913 and 2014 crests. The crest's shield retains the three points at the top but is in a more traditional shape. No lettering or numbering features on the new club crest, just like that which was used on home shirts the previous 2014\u201315 season.\n\nOn 4 May 2017 at [[Portsmouth Guildhall]], The Tornante Company, owned by Michael Eisner met the Pompey Supporters Trust (PST), the fan-based owners of Portsmouth, to discuss a potential takeover of the football club. During the meeting, the prospective new owners identified a long overlooked ownership and copyright issue concerning the traditional Portsmouth crest \u2013 Portsmouth Football Club did not legally \"own\" the symbols on the crest, which had actually only been \"on loan\" to the club from Portsmouth City Council since 1913.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0n7DZY79jTY |publisher=The Tornante Company |via=YouTube.com |title=Michael Eisner's Q&A Session with Portsmouth Supporters Trust |date=13 May 2017 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe Tornante Company completed their purchase of Portsmouth on 3 August 2017 after a majority vote from members of the Pompey Supporters Trust to sell.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} To rectify the copyright and commercial marketing issues with the current 2015 crest, the decision was taken by the new owners to design and copyright a brand new crest for the future.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} Portsmouth's fans were consulted by traditional and digital media during late 2017 and early 2018 with various designs for new crests. Most of the designs were minor tweaks and adjustments of the existing 2015 crest, just enough to make a new crest design different from that of Portsmouth City Council's coat of Arms.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nOn 15 March 2018, two newly redesigned club crests were finally revealed. Both new crests featured a new eight pointed nautical compass star and the addition of an \"1898\" date, the founding year of the football club, beneath the crescent moon. The new crests are to be copyrighted and introduced for the new 2018\u201319 season. The first new crest, similar to previous crests, is intended for players shirts. The second crest, surrounded by a blue ring with \"Portsmouth Football Club\" written in it, will be used for letterheads, merchandise and other commercial purposes.<ref name=\"portsmouthfc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Home colours==\n{|\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _claretborder|\n pattern_b = _Roma2|\n pattern_ra = _claretborder|\n pattern_sh = |\n pattern_so = |\n leftarm = ff9999|\n body = ff9999|\n rightarm = ff9999|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n socks = 000000|\n title = 1899\u20131909\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _collar|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = FFFFFF|\n body         = FFFFFF|\n rightarm = FFFFFF|\n shorts = 003366|\n socks = 003366|\n title = 1909\u20131912\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _collarwhite|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = 0066FF|\n body         = 0066FF|\n rightarm = 0066FF|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n pattern_so = _2 white stripes|\n socks = 000000|\n title = 1912\u20131933\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _collarwhite|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n pattern_so = _2 white stripes|\n socks = 000000|\n title = 1933\u20131947\n}}\n|}\n\nIn their first 1899\u20131900 season in the Southern League Division One, Portsmouth's first home colours were salmon pink shirts with maroon collars and cuffs, matched with white shorts and black socks.  The pink shirts gave the early Portsmouth F.C. the alternative second nickname of 'The Shrimps'. The collars and cuffs were the same colour as the Corporation of Portsmouth's public trams, which were painted maroon at the time.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm |title=Portsmouth |publisher=Historical Football Kits |website=historicalkits.co.uk |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref> These colours lasted until the end of the 1908\u201309 season. 'The Shrimps' nickname then also declined from common usage.\n\nAt the start of the 1909\u201310 season, Portsmouth changed to white shirts with navy blue shorts and navy blue socks. The next season, Portsmouth ended the poor 1910\u201311 season in bottom place and Portsmouth were relegated to Southern League Division Two. Following relegation, a financial crisis, fund raising, promotion in early 1912 and then another financial crisis, the original Portsmouth company that had been formed in 1898 was 'wound up'. A new limited company was formed on 27 July 1912 as Portsmouth F.C.'s parent company.\n\nFor the start of the 1912\u201313 Southern League Division One season, Portsmouth changed their home colours to azure blue shirts, white shorts and black socks. This was to become Portsmouth's home kit colour combination up until the start of the 1933\u201334 season, when the shirts were changed to a royal blue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm|title=Portsmouth - Historical Football Kits|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk}}</ref> These colours remained until the start of the 1947\u201348 season, when the black socks were changed to red; this coinciding with the club's most successful period and has remained the favoured colours for the majority of the time since.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pompey's Home Kits Through The Ages |url=http://www.pompeyweb.co.uk/kits.htm |publisher=PompeyWeb |accessdate=27 August 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603114751/http://www.pompeyweb.co.uk/kits.htm |archivedate=3 June 2008}}</ref> Portsmouth F.C. changed their colour combination several times during the 1966\u20131976 period, before reverting to the now tradition post-war blue shirts, white shorts and red stockings in 1976.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> For the club's 110th anniversary season in 2008\u201309, Portsmouth played in an all blue home kit, which debuted in the previous season's successful 2008 FA Cup Final win.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Since the 2009\u201310 season, Portsmouth reverted to the now traditional blue-white-red home kit.\n\n===Red socks memorial===\n{|\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _collarwhite|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n socks = FF0000|\n title = 1947\u20131966\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _whiteborder|\n pattern_b = _whitecollar|\n pattern_ra = _whiteborder|\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n shorts = 0000FF|\n pattern_so = _whitehorizontal|\n socks = 0000FF|\n title = 1966\u20131972\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _whiteborder|\n pattern_b = _whitecollar|\n pattern_ra = _whiteborder|\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n pattern_sh = _blue stripes|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n pattern_so = _whitehorizontal|\n socks = 0000FF|\n title = 1972\u20131973\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _blueborder|\n pattern_b = _pfcaway10|\n pattern_ra = _blueborder|\n leftarm = FFFFFF|\n body = |\n rightarm = FFFFFF|\n shorts = 0000FF|\n pattern_so = _bluehorizontal|\n socks = FFFFFF|\n title = 1973\u20131976\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = |\n pattern_b = _vneckwhite|\n pattern_ra = |\n leftarm = 0000FF|\n body         = 0000FF|\n rightarm = 0000FF|\n shorts = FFFFFF|\n socks = FF0000|\n title = 1976\u20132008\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _whiteline|\n pattern_b  = _pfcccc|\n pattern_ra = _whiteline|\n leftarm    = 0000FF|\n body       = 0000FF|\n rightarm   = 0000FF|\n shorts     = 0000FF|\n socks      = 0000FF|\n title      = 2008\u20132009\n}}\n|}\nPortsmouth had predominantly worn black socks since their first match in 1899 up until the end of the post-World War II 1946\u201347 FA Cup season \u2013 in which the Football League had not yet resumed.\n\nDuring the Second World War and post-war periods, the British Army's [[Bernard Montgomery|Field Marshal Sir Bernard 'Monty' Montgomery]] had been based at [[Southwick House]], 5 miles to the north of Portsmouth. Montgomery regularly attended war-time League South matches at Fratton Park, becoming the honorary President of Portsmouth Football Club. Following the suggestion by Montgomery, red socks were introduced by the club as a memorial to soldiers lost in wartime as red is the traditional colour of the British Army and also the colour of the [[Remembrance poppy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2013/may/crest-of-a-wave/ |title=Crest Of A Wave |publisher=Portsmouth Football Club |date=22 May 2013 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nWith the resumption of a full professional Football League season in England in 1947\u201348, Portsmouth changed their socks from the usual black to red for the start of the 1947\u201348 season. This also gave the Portsmouth team a patriotic blue, white and red appearance similar to the United Kingdom's red white and blue [[Union Flag]].\n\nThe new red socks also coincided with Portsmouth's most successful period, as the club won two consecutive top-tier division (now 'Premier League') title honours in [[1948\u201349 Football League|1948\u201349]] and [[1949\u201350 Football League|1949\u201350]], so the red socks were retained for good luck.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===Away colours===\nThe most frequent away colours used by Portsmouth have been white shirts with royal or navy blue shorts and either blue or white socks.<ref name=\"historicalkits.co.uk\"/> The club has had white as either the second or third choice shirt for every season since 1998\u201399 to date.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} Other colours that have appeared several times on Portsmouth change kits have been yellow (usually with blue shorts) and red (often combined with black).{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} From the 2006\u201307 season to the 2008\u201309 season the club have used black with a gold trim as their third choice colours.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} In the 2009\u201310 season the third kit was black with blue trim and thin blue hoops.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} The away kit was white with two navy blue vertical lines running the whole way down the side of the shirt, with the badge superimposed on top of them.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} The home kit has been the classic red white and blue kit, with plain blue shirt, plain white shorts and plain red socks.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}} For the [[2010 FA Cup Final]], Portsmouth wore a change kit of white shirts, burgundy shorts and burgundy socks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/7719775/FA-Cup-final-Chelsea-v-Portsmouth-preview.html|title=FA Cup final: Chelsea v Portsmouth preview|date=14 May 2010|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> For 2010\u201311, the away kit was a white shirt, with maroon shorts and socks (image below). In 2011\u201312, the away kit was a black shirt, with black shorts and socks; the club also announced a third one, with a divided shirt half-black and half-red; shorts and socks were black. For 2012\u201313, the club returned with a white shirt as an away kit, and turned into an orange-type third kit, with black shorts and orange socks.\n\nFor the 2017\u201318 season, Portsmouth had two away kits. The first choice away kit had white shirts, blue shorts and blue socks. The second choice was an all navy blue strip with pink collars, cuffs and other trim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2017/july/201718-away-kit-now-on-sale/ |title=2017/18 Away Kit: Now On Sale |work=Portsmouth F.C. |date=27 July 2017 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2017/august/201718-third-kit-now-on-sale/ |title=2017/18 Third Kit: Now On Sale |work=Portsmouth F.C. |date=3 August 2017 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFor 2018\u201319 season, sportswear manufacturer Nike produced a first-choice away kit of white shirts with a blue v-neck and blue shoulders, trimmed with blue sleeve cuffs. The shorts and socks are plain blue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2018/july/pompey-unveil-201819-away-kit/ |title=Pompey Unveil 2018/19 Away Kit |work=Portsmouth F.C.  |date=13 July 2018 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref> An all-black third kit was revealed on 13 August 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2018/august/pompey-reveal-201819-third-kit/ |title=Pompey Reveal 2018/19 Third Kit |work=Portsmouth F.C. |date=13 August 2018 |accessdate=23 October 2018 }}</ref> to avoid clashing with other teams such as [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] who wear blue and white quartered shirts as their first choice home kit colours.\n\nFor 2019-20, Portsmouth revealed on 5 July 2019 an all purple-indigo third kit, based on Nike's ''Park Derby II SS'' template.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kitlocker.com/products/results,1-0?error=404|title=All Products &#124; Football, Rugby, Gym &#124; Kitlocker.com 404 The requested product does not exist.|website=www.kitlocker.com}}</ref> The third kit had a purple shirt with white shoulder stripe and cuffs, purple shorts with white side stripes, and purple socks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2019/july/pompey-launch-201920-third-kit/|title=Pompey Launch 2019/20 Third Kit|website=www.portsmouthfc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Other historic kits===\n\n{|\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _whiteline\n| pattern_b  = _pfcccc\n| pattern_ra = _whiteline\n| leftarm    = 0000FF\n| body       = 0000FF\n| rightarm   = 0000FF\n| shorts     = 0000FF\n| socks      = 0000FF\n| title      = [[2008 FA Cup Final]]\n}}\n|{{Football kit |\n pattern_la = _pompey1011a|\n pattern_b = _pompey1011a|\n pattern_ra = _pompey1011a|\n leftarm = fe8e7a|\n body         = 86202e|\n rightarm = fe8e7a|\n shorts = 800000|\n socks = 800000|\n title = [[2010 FA Cup Final]] (Away)\n}}\n|}\n\nFor the [[2007\u201308 FA Cup|2008 FA Cup Final]] victory against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], Portsmouth debuted an all blue home kit manufactured by [[Canterbury of New Zealand|Canterbury]] and sponsored by [[Oki Electric Industry|Oki Printing Solutions]] to commemorate the club's 110th Anniversary year. The all blue home kit was also used throughout the following 2008\u201309 season.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nPortsmouth again reached the [[2009\u201310 FA Cup|FA Cup Final in 2010]], but were defeated 1\u20130 by [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. Portsmouth, as the away team, wore a white and maroon kit inspired from elements of the original \"Shrimps\" era (1899\u20131909) kit in which maroon collars and cuffs featured on the salmon pink home shirts.\n\n===Kit manufacturers and sponsors===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!Years\n!Manufacturers\n!Shirt sponsors (front)\n!Shirt sponsors (back)\n|-\n|1976\u20131977\n|[[Umbro]]\n|rowspan=5|''No sponsors''\n|rowspan=18|''No sponsors''\n|-\n|1978\u20131980\n|[[Admiral Sportswear|Admiral]]\n|-\n|1980\u20131983\n|[[Gola (manufacturer)|Gola]]\n|-\n|1983\u20131984\n|[[Le Coq Sportif]]\n|-\n|1985\u20131987\n|[[Umbro]]\n|-\n|1987\u20131989\n|[[Admiral Sportswear|Admiral]]\n|[[Fiat]]\n|-\n|1989\u20131991\n|Scoreline\n|rowspan=3|[[Goodmans Industries|Goodmans]]\n|-\n|1991\u20131993\n|Influence\n|-\n|1993\u20131995\n|rowspan=2|[[ASICS]]\n|-\n|1995\u20131997\n|[[The News (Portsmouth)|The News]]\n|-\n|1997\u20131999\n|[[Admiral Sportswear|Admiral]]\n|KJC Mobile Phones\n|-\n|1999\u20132000\n|rowspan=3|Pompey Sport <sup>1</sup>\n|The Pompey Centre\n|-\n|2000\u20132002\n|Bishop's Printers\n|-\n|2002\u20132005\n|[[Ty Inc.|TY Europe]]\n|-\n|2005\u20132007\n|[[Jako]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Oki Electric Industry|OKI]]\n|-\n|2007\u20132009\n|rowspan=2|[[Canterbury of New Zealand|Canterbury]]\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|rowspan=4|Jobsite.co.uk\n|-\n|2010\u20132011\n|[[Kappa (company)|Kappa]]\n|-\n|2011\u20132013\n|[[Kappa (company)|Kappa]]\n|rowspan=3|Covers Timber & Builders Merchants <sup>2</sup>\n|-\n|2013\u20132018\n|[[Sondico]]\n|-\n|2018\u20132021\n|[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n|rowspan=3|[[University of Portsmouth]]\n|}\n\n'''<sup>1</sup>''' Portsmouth's own manufacturer.<br />\n'''<sup>2</sup>''' As from 2011\u201312 season, sponsors were added to the back of EFL clubs shirts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pompeyshirts.co.uk/history/ |title=Shirt History |work=Pompey Shirts |accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==\"Pompey\" nickname==\nPortsmouth Football Club are traditionally nicknamed '''''Pompey''''', a nickname already long associated with the English city of Portsmouth and its [[HMNB Portsmouth|Royal Navy base]]. An exact origin for the ''Pompey'' nickname has never formally been identified by historians, as many variations, sources and interpretations of the ''Pompey'' nickname exist.\n\nOne possible theory of the Pompey nickname is the [[Contraction (grammar)|grammatical contraction]] of the [[Old Portsmouth]] location name '''[[Portsmouth Point]]''' to the shorter '''Po'm. P.''' ('''Po''''''rts'''''m.'''''outh'' '''P.'''''oint'') which supposedly saved time and space when handwritten into a ship's logbook. Other theories include Royal Navy romanticism of the Roman character '''[[Pompey]]''' from [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Antony and Cleopatra]]'', used by officers to inspire the ship's company.\n\nAnother ''Pompey'' nickname theory, based on actual historic events, originates from {{HMS|Pompee|1793|6}}, originally a newly built [[T\u00e9m\u00e9raire-class ship of the line|T\u00e9m\u00e9raire class]] French frigate named ''La Pomp\u00e9e'' that was surrendered by French Royalists during the [[French Revolution]] to their British allies during the [[Siege of Toulon]] in 1793. The ship ''La Pomp\u00e9e'' eventually arrived at [[Spithead]] in 1794 and was recommissioned into the Royal Navy as ''HMS Pomp\u00e9e''.  In 1797, HMS ''Pomp\u00e9e'' was one of sixteen ships involved in the [[Spithead and Nore mutinies]] of 1797. During her later career, HMS ''Pomp\u00e9e'' also served as Portsmouth's guard ship and ended her career in the early nineteenth century anchored in [[Portsmouth Harbour]] as the chief prison ship ''Pompee''. ''Pompee'' was also used as prison ship for French prisoners captured during the [[Napoleonic Wars]] (1803\u20131815). The harsh treatment received aboard ''Pompee'' gained a national notoriety with the criminal classes of England, the name ''Pompey'' itself became a northern England slang word for prison.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/notesandqueries/query/0,5753,-2010,00.html?gusrc=gpd |title=Why is Portsmouth called Pompey? |work=The Guardian |author=David Francis |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> The ''Pompee'' became a familiar local landmark and gained a common association with the Royal Navy and the civilian Portsmouth population, who both then began associating ''Pompee'' with Portsmouth. ''Pompee'' was finally taken away to be broken up in [[Woolwich]] in 1817, but her name lived on in Portsmouth folklore, anglicised to \"''Pompey''\" over time.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe present Portsmouth Football Club were not the first football club in the city of Portsmouth to be known as ''Pompey''. In the 1890s, an amateur Portsmouth-based British Army team, '''Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C.''' were reported in newspapers with the ''Pompey'' nickname, as well as also being known as ''The Gunners''.  Royal Artillery Portsmouth's supporters were also responsible for creating [[Portsmouth F.C.#'The Pompey Chimes'|\"The Town Hall Chimes\"]] chant, which later became known as ''\"The Pompey Chimes\"'' chant in the twentieth century.  The chant originally began at Royal Artillery Portsmouth's home football ground at Burnaby Road, Portsmouth ([[United Services Recreation Ground]]) and was within easy earshot of the nearby Portsmouth Town Hall (now called [[Portsmouth Guildhall]]) clock bells, which had inspired the chant.\n\nRoyal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C. were disqualified for \"professionalism\" after an 1898\u201399 FA Amateur Cup match.  Royal Artillery were also forced to field only a team of amateur reserve players, thus weakening the remaining Royal Artillery team for the remainder of the 1898\u201399 Southern Football League season. Royal Artillery finished bottom of the [[1898\u201399 Southern Football League#Division One|table]], relegated after a relegation match with Cowes F.C. and were eventually disbanded. The \"Pompey\" nickname, the \"Town Hall Chimes\" chant, some of the Royal Artillery players and their supporters then migrated to a newly formed football club, named Portsmouth F.C., earlier formed on 5 April 1898.<ref name=\"portsmouth.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/heritage/history-of-the-chimes-1-1299340|title=History of the chimes|website=Portsmouth.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nPortsmouth F.C., as the \"new\" Pompey, played their first Southern Football League match away to Chatham Town on Saturday 2 September 1899, winning 0\u20131. Their first home match at Fratton Park stadium took place only four days later on Wednesday 6 September 1899, a friendly match against Southampton F.C., which Portsmouth won 2\u20130. During the first early seasons of Portsmouth F.C., the football team wore salmon pink shirts with maroon collars and cuffs, white shorts and black socks. The pink shirts gave rise to an alternative nickname, ''''The Shrimps''''. 'The Shrimps' went out of common usage after 1909 when Portsmouth F.C. began playing in white shirts, navy blue shorts and navy blue stockings. After the original 1898 founding company was replaced in 1912, Portsmouth began playing in their now familiar blue shirts in the 1912\u201313 season.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==Stadium==\n[[File:Fratton Park entrance.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The entrance to Fratton Park's South Stand, with its mock Tudor facade]]\n{{main|Fratton Park}}\nPortsmouth F.C. play their home games at Fratton Park, in the district of [[Milton, Portsmouth]]. The stadium has been home to the club throughout its entire history since the club formed in 1898. Fratton Park is affectionately nicknamed \"The Old Girl\" by Portsmouth F.C. supporters.\n\nPlans for relocation were first mooted in the early 1990s, but due to various objections and financial obstacles, the club has continued to play at Fratton Park. Most recently, plans for relocation have included new stadia on a site offered by the [[Royal Navy]] at [[Horsea Island]], between Stamshaw and Port Solent, and on reclaimed land in Portsmouth Harbour beside the existing naval base. The former was mooted as a possible [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] venue as part of England's bid process. However, the cost to the city's taxpayers to join the bid was deemed too great a risk to take.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8378313.stm |title=Football \u2013 Portsmouth pulls out of 2018 bid |publisher=BBC News |date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> A third, oft returned-to option, is to build a new stadium on the site of the existing Fratton Park.\n\nFollowing Portsmouth F.C.'s financial troubles, subsequent relegation from the Premier League, and the failure of the England 2018 bid, as of May 2017 there are no active plans for a new club stadium.\n\n==Supporters and rivalries==\n{{main|South Coast derby}}\n[[File:Pompeywembley.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Portsmouth fans at Wembley Stadium for the 2007\u201308 FA Cup semi-final with West Bromwich Albion]]\nPortsmouth's main rivals are [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], who are 19.8 miles (31.8&nbsp;km) away, with the \"border\" between the two located in the Hampshire village of [[Titchfield]].  The [[South Coast Derby]] is one of the less frequently played rivalries within English football due to the clubs being in different divisions however this usually adds to the ferocity of the fixture.\n\nPrior to the mid/late 1960s, rivalry between Portsmouth and Southampton was largely non-existent, as a consequence of their disparity in league status. This [[Local derby|derby match]] has been sporadic. Since 1977, the teams have only played league games against each other in four seasons (1987\u201388, 2003\u201304, 2004\u201305 and 2011\u201312). Including Southern League games, there have been 64 league games between the clubs, but they have also met five times in the FA Cup, Portsmouth beating their rivals 4\u20131 at [[St Mary's Stadium]] in their last meeting in 2010, and twice in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] \u2013 with Southampton winning both times.\n\nMany Portsmouth supporters commonly use the derogatory nickname '''''Scummer''''' (plural: '''''Scummers''''') to describe Southampton fans, or collectively '''''Scum''''' to also include their football club, and indeed the city of Southampton itself.\n* A disproven common origin theory dating from the late twentieth century suggested that the ''Scum'' nickname was an acronym of ''Southampton Company of Union Men'', linked to a vague recollection of an unspecified and unsourced past dockers strike, in which Southampton-based dockers supposedly crossed Portsmouth dockyard picket lines when brought in as [[Strikebreaker|scab labour]] to work inside the naval base. This theory is almost certainly an urban myth, as Royal Navy dockers are not permitted to go on strike.\n* Victorian era dockers employed in the supposedly higher status [[HMNB Portsmouth|Portsmouth Royal Dockyard]], looked down in disdain upon the civilian merchant port dockers at [[Port of Southampton|Southampton Docks]] and nicknamed them ''Scum'', as scum, flotsam and jetsam are useless residue found floating on, or nearby water.\n* According to the Oxford English Dictionary, ''Scummers'' was a derogatory name with naval origins for pirates or buccaneers, and was first recorded in use in 1585.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/scummer |title=scummer |work=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=24 January 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/jan/23/newsstory.sport8 |title=Scummers v Skates |work=The Guardian |author=Kevin Mitchell |date=23 January 2005 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Portsmouth supporters have had the equally derogatory nickname '''''Skate''''' bestowed upon them by Southampton fans as a rebuttal to ''Scummer'' since the 1987\u201388 Division One season. This was unofficially chosen by Southampton fans from a list of insults compiled by a Southampton-based supporters fanzine called ''The Ugly Inside'' in 1988.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fansnetwork.co.uk/football/southampton/news/48841/ |title=Why Bournemouth Will Never Be Saints Rivals ! |work=FansNetwork |date=17 October 2018 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Ironically, the chosen nickname ''Skate'' was actually stolen from the civilian population of Portsmouth, who had long used ''Skate'' as a derogatory insult or nickname for sailors based in Portsmouth Dockyard and other Royal Navy establishments. According to legend and folklore, Royal Navy matelots on long sea voyages were regularly denied female company, and would keep a [[Skate (fish)|skate]] (fish species) in their hammock or bunkside, as the mouth of the skate was supposedly used as a substitute vagina. Sailors ashore in Royal Navy uniform seeking the services of Portsmouth's prostitutes would often be refused service and met with a ''\"I ain't no skate bait, mate!\"'' rebuttal.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\nAnother rivalry over the years, colloquially known as the \"Dockyard Derby\", is with [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/7201902.stm|title=Naval support for Dockyard Derby|date=22 January 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2289954/Tynan-Plymouth-can-cause-derby-upset.html|title=Tynan: Plymouth can cause derby upset|date=25 January 2008|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> This rivalry is also known as the Battle of the Ports.<ref name=harvey>{{cite book |title=Rivals: The Off-Beat Guide to the 92 League Clubs |last1=Harvey |first1=Geoff |last2=Strowger |first2=Vanessa |year=2004 |publisher=Aesculus Press Ltd |location=Swadlincote, Derbyshire |isbn=1-904328-13-X |page=133 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mG7XLIPEHvAC&pg=PT111&dq=%22battle+of+the+ports%22+football |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> In recent seasons the club has also developed a minor rivalry with [[Sunderland AFC|Sunderland]], mainly stemming from the clubs meeting each other 5 times in the 18/19 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-portsmouth-story-so-far-16284128|title=Sunderland vs Portsmouth: A story of red cards, penalties and a simmering rivalry|first=Sean|last=Tighe|date=16 May 2019|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n\nLesser rivalries exist with fellow South Coast clubs [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], [[Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton and Hove Albion]] and South London club [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].\n\n==='The Pompey Chimes'===\nThe best-known chant sung by Portsmouth supporters are \"The Pompey Chimes\". The chant is regarded as football's oldest chant still in use today.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew|last=Pettie|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/7821392/An-ode-to-footballs-rowdy-poets.html|title=An ode to football's rowdy poets|date=11 June 2010|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=McCallum>{{cite book |title=Glory Gunners: The History of Royal Artillery FC Portsmouth |first=Kevin |last=Smith |year=1999 |publisher=K.Smith |location=London |isbn=0-9534707-0-9 |page=69}}</ref>\n\n\"The Pompey Chimes\" were originally called \"The Town Hall Chimes\", and were created by the supporters of '''Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) Football Club''', a British Army artillery regiment team, who were the most popular and successful amateur football team based in Portsmouth for much of the 1890s. Royal Artillery played their home matches at the [[United Services Recreation Ground]] in Burnaby Road, Portsmouth,<ref name=\"portsmouth.co.uk\"/> and were already nicknamed \"Pompey\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hoppingaroundhampshire.blogspot.com/2013/04/39-united-services-portsmouth-fc.html|title=Hopping Around Hampshire: 39. United Services Portsmouth FC|first=Andrew|last=Ormerod|date=9 April 2013}}</ref> before the founding of Portsmouth F.C. in 1898.\n\nThe nearby Portsmouth Town Hall (now called the [[Portsmouth Guildhall]]), only 0.3 miles (0.5&nbsp;km) from Burnaby Road was completed in 1890, and would strike the various [[Westminster Quarters]] chimes every quarter hour. Football referees would use the Town Hall's clock bells as a reference to when the football match should end at 4&nbsp;pm. Just before 4&nbsp;pm the crowd of supporters would slowly lilt in unison with the Town Hall's chimes on the hour to encourage the referee to blow the whistle to signify full-time. The original words to 'The Pompey Chimes' (as printed in the 1900\u201301 Official Handbook of Portsmouth F.C.), were:\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\"> \\relative c' {    \\time 5/4 \\key e \\major e4 gis fis b,2 | e4 fis gis e2 | gis4 e fis b,2 |  b4 fis' gis e2 | R1*5/4\\fermataMarkup  \\bar \"||\"  \\clef bass \\time 4/4 e,1^\"Portsmouth Town Hall Chimes (4pm)\"  | e1| e1 | e1 |}</score>\n<!--[[File:Westminster Quarter 4.svg|frameless|upright=3.17]]\n<br>[[File:Westminster Big Ben.svg|frameless|upright=0.83]] ( Big&nbsp;Ben)-->\n\n''Play up Pompey,''<br />\n''Just one more goal!'' <br />\n''Make tracks! What ho!''<br />\n''Hallo! Hallo!!''\n\nWith the demise of Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C. after their expulsion from the 1898\u201399 [[FA Amateur Cup]] for alleged professionalism, many of Royal Artillery's supporters switched their allegiance in 1899 to Portsmouth F.C., taking the \"Town Hall Chimes\" chant and the \"Pompey\" nickname from Burnaby Road to [[Fratton Park]], a distance of 1.8 miles (2.8&nbsp;km).\n\nThe Pompey Chimes are still sung at Fratton Park today, and have evolved to be sung at a quicker tempo, and with a shortened chime style \u2013 usually twice:\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\"> \\relative c'' {\\time 5/4  \\key e \\major gis4 e fis b,2 | b4 fis' gis e2 | gis4 e fis b,2 | b4 fis' gis e2 |}</score>\n<!--[[File:Westminster Quarter 3.svg|frameless|upright=2.56]]-->\n\n''Play up Pompey,''<br />\n''Pompey play up!''<br />\n''Play up Pompey,''<br />\n''Pompey play up!''\n\n==Portsmouth in Europe==\n{{main|Portsmouth F.C. in European football}}\n\nPortsmouth made their European debut in the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Cup]]. After a home victory against [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]] and a home draw against [[A.C. Milan]], Portsmouth were knocked out at the group stages after a 3\u20132 away loss to [[VfL Wolfsburg]].\n\n==Women's football==\nThe club's female counterpart is [[Portsmouth F.C. Ladies|Portsmouth F.C. Womens]], which was founded in 1987. The team currently plays in the [[FA Women's Premier League National Division]], after having won the [[FA Women's Premier League Southern Division]] in 2012. Pompey are the current holders of the Hampshire Cup. Following the takeover of Portsmouth F.C. by the Portsmouth Supporters Trust, it was announced that there would be closer ties between the men's and women's clubs.\n\n==Affiliated clubs==\nPortsmouth have had a long-standing relationship with [[Havant & Waterlooville F.C.|Havant & Waterlooville]], with regular pre-season friendlies organised between the two clubs. Portsmouth have also previously used [[West Leigh Park]], Havant & Waterlooville's home stadium, for reserve team matches. Previous links with Belgian side [[S.V. Zulte Waregem|Zulte Waregem]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=554308&sec=england&cc=5739 |title=Portsmouth strike deal with Zulte Waregem|publisher=ESPN FC |date=9 July 2008 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> and Irish academy [[Home Farm F.C.|Home Farm]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouth.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=144840|title=Pompey announce link-up with Home Farm|publisher=portsmouth.vitalfootball.co.uk|date=23 February 2009}}</ref> have been cancelled.\n\nPortsmouth have developed a relationship with [[Gosport Borough F.C.|Gosport Borough]] after their promotion to the Conference South. Portsmouth fans were encouraged to support Gosport in their FA Trophy final match at Wembley in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/article/blues-backing-borough-1430566.aspx?pd=635308236000000000|title=Blues Backing Borough|publisher=Portsmouth F.C.}}</ref> They also play friendlies and loan out players to the side.\n\n==Club honours==\nSource for honours:<ref name=History>{{cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/club/history/|title=History|website=Portsmouth FC.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===League competitions===\n; [[Football League First Division]] (1888\u20131992) > [[Premier League]] (1992\u2013present)\n* '''Champions (2):''' [[1948\u201349 Football League|1948\u201349]], [[1949\u201350 Football League|1949\u201350]]\n\n; [[Football League Second Division]] (1892\u20131992) > [[Football League First Division]] (1992\u20132004) > [[EFL Championship]] (2004\u2013present)\n* '''Champions (1):''' [[2002\u201303 Football League|2002\u201303]]\n* Runners-up (2): [[1926\u201327 Football League|1926\u201327]], [[1986\u201387 Football League|1986\u201387]]\n\n; [[Football League Third Division South]] (1921\u20131958) > [[Football League Third Division]] (1958\u20131992) > [[EFL League One]] (2004\u2013present)\n* '''Champions (3):''' [[1923\u201324 Football League|1923\u201324 (South)]], [[1961\u201362 Football League|1961\u201362]], [[1982\u201383 Football League|1982\u201383]]\n\n;[[EFL League Two]] (2004\u2013present)\n* '''Champions (1):''' [[2016\u201317 EFL League Two|2016\u201317]]\n\n===Cup competitions===\n;[[FA Cup]]\n* '''Winners (2):''' [[1939 FA Cup Final|1938\u201339]], [[2008 FA Cup Final|2007\u201308]]\n* Runners-up (3): [[1929 FA Cup Final|1928\u201329]], [[1934 FA Cup Final|1933\u201334]], [[2010 FA Cup Final|2009\u201310]]\n\n;[[FA Community Shield]]\n* '''Winners (1):''' [[1949 FA Charity Shield|1949]] (shared)\n* Runners-up (1): [[2008 FA Community Shield|2008]]\n\n;[[EFL Trophy]] \n* '''Winners (1):''' [[2019 EFL Trophy Final|2018\u201319]]\n* Finalists (TBD): [[2020 EFL Trophy Final|2019\u201320]]\n\n;[[Hampshire Senior Cup]]\n* '''Winners (4):''' 1903, 1913, 1952, 1987\n* Runners-up (4): 1900, 1904, 1905, 1959\n\n===Lower league competitions===\n; [[Southern Football League|Southern Football League First Division]]\n* '''Champions (2):''' [[1901\u201302 Southern Football League|1901\u201302 (not elected for promotion)]], [[1919\u201320 Southern Football League|1919\u201320]] {{Efn|Portsmouth became founder members of the inaugural [[Football League Third Division]] in 1920.}}\n* Runners-up (2): [[1899\u20131900 Southern Football League|1899\u20131900]], [[1906\u201307 Southern Football League|1906\u20131907]]\n\n; [[Southern Football League|Southern Football League Second Division]]\n* Runners-up (1): [[1911\u201312 Southern Football League|1911\u201312]]\n\n; [[Western Football League|Western Football League First Division]]\n* '''Champions (3):''' [[1900\u201301 Western Football League|1900\u201301]], [[1901\u201302 Western Football League|1901\u201302]], [[1902\u201303 Western Football League|1902\u201303]]\n\n===Other/friendly honours===\n\n;[[London War Cup]] (replaced by [[Football League War Cup]])\n* Runners-up (1): 1942\n\n;[[Premier League Asia Trophy]]\n* '''Winners (1):''' [[2007 Premier League Asia Trophy|2007]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/2632222/pompey-win-asia-trophy |title=Pompey win Asia Trophy |publisher=Sky Sports |author=Peter Fraser |accessdate=11 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/402272 |title=History of the Premier League Asia Trophy |publisher=The Premier League |date=25 May 2017 |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n;[[Edmonton Cup]]\n* '''Winners (1):''' [[Edmonton Cup|2010]]<ref>http://www.portsmouth-mad.co.uk/feat/edy9/portsmouth_season_review_20102011_preseason_677836/index.shtml</ref>\n\n==Club records==\n* Home attendance record: '''51,385''' v [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], [[1948\u201349 FA Cup|1949 FA Cup Fifth Round]], 26 February 1949, [[Fratton Park]]\n* Away attendance record: '''99,370''' v [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]], [[1938\u201339 FA Cup|1939 FA Cup Final]], 29 April 1939, [[Wembley Stadium (1923)]]\n* Current [[Wembley Stadium]] attendance record for a football match: '''89,874''' (90,000 capacity), [[2008 FA Cup Final]], 17 May 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/10993576/which-wembley-records-could-tottenham-break-this-season |title=Which Wembley records could Tottenham break this season? |work=Sky Sports |author=Adam Smith |date=18 August 2017 |accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n* Record victory: '''9\u20131''' v [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], [[Football League Second Division|Division 2]], 9 April 1927\n* Record defeat: '''0\u201310''' v [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], [[Football League First Division|Division 1]], 20 October 1928\n* Highest scoring game: '''7\u20134''' v [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], [[Premier League]], 29 September 2007\n* Most consecutive wins (all competitions): '''9''' (4 January 2020 - 8 February 2020) <ref>https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/matches/results/</ref>\n* Most appearances for club: '''834''' [[Jimmy Dickinson]], 1946\u201365\n* Most league goals for club: '''194''' [[Peter Harris (footballer)|Peter Harris]], 1946\u20131960\n* Most league goals in a season: '''42''' [[Guy Whittingham]], 1992/93\n* Most goals for club: '''211''' [[Peter Harris (footballer)|Peter Harris]], 1946\u201360\n* Most international caps whilst at club: '''48''' [[Jimmy Dickinson|Jimmy Dickinson (England)]]\n* Transfer record (received): '''\u00a318&nbsp;million''' from [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] for [[Lassana Diarra]] December 2008\n* Transfer record (paid): '''\u00a311&nbsp;million''' to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] for [[Peter Crouch]], July 2008\n\n===Record signing===\nOn 11 July 2008, Portsmouth completed the club-record signing&nbsp;\u2013 thought to be around \u00a311&nbsp;million&nbsp;\u2013 of [[England national football team|England]] striker [[Peter Crouch]] in a four-year deal from Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web |title=Portsmouth agree Peter Crouch transfer fee |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/liverpool/2305024/Portsmouth-agree-Peter-Crouch-transfer-fee.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=7 July 2008|accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> This marked the second time Crouch had been Portsmouth's most expensive player as in 2001 his \u00a31.5&nbsp;million fee was a club record. Portsmouth's first million-pound signing was [[Rory Allen]] in July 1999.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pompey swoop for Spurs striker |url=http://archive.andoveradvertiser.co.uk/1999/7/15/90597.html |newspaper=Andover Advertiser |date=15 July 1999|accessdate=27 August 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108194850/http://archive.andoveradvertiser.co.uk/1999/7/15/90597.html|archivedate=8 January 2009}}</ref> The highest fee received was \u00a318&nbsp;million for midfielder [[Lassana Diarra]] from [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/portsmouth/3811291/Portsmouth-accept-exceptional-Real-Madrid-bid-for-Lassana-Diarra.html|title=Portsmouth accept exceptional Real Madrid bid for Lassana Diarra|work=The Telegraph |first=Jeremy |last=Wilson |date=17 December 2008 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Portsmouth FC}}\n\n===Official websites===\n* {{Official website|http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk}}\n* [http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2009/clubs/club=84297/matches/index.html Portsmouth F.C.] at the [[UEFA]] official website\n\n===News sites===\n{{BBC football info|portsmouth|Portsmouth F.C.}}\n* [http://www.skysports.com/football/teams/portsmouth Portsmouth F.C. news] from [[Sky Sports]]\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite book| ref = harv  | first = Simon  | last = Inglis  | title = Football Grounds of Britain  | year = 1996  | publisher = Collins Willow  | isbn = 0-00-218426-5  }}\n* {{cite book\n| first=Colin |last=Farmery\n| title=Portsmouth: the Modern Era \u2013 a Complete Record\n| publisher=Desert Island Books\n| year=2005\n| isbn=1-905328-08-7}}\n* {{cite book\n| first=Colin |last=Farmery\n| title=Portsmouth: From Tindall to Ball \u2013 A Complete Record\n| publisher=Desert Island Books\n| year=1999\n| isbn=1-874287-25-2}}\n* {{cite book\n| first=Colin |last=Farmery\n| title=Seventeen Miles From Paradise \u2013 Saints v Pompey: Passion, Pride and Prejudice\n| publisher=Desert Island Books\n| year=2004\n| isbn=1-874287-89-9}}\n* {{cite book\n| first1=Cass |last1=Pennant|first2=Rob |last2=Silvester\n| title=Rolling with the 6.57 Crew \u2013 The True Story of Pompey's Legendary Football Fans\n| publisher=John Blake Publishing\n| year=2004\n| isbn=1-84454-072-3}}\n\n{{Portsmouth F.C.}}\n{{Portsmouth F.C. seasons}}\n{{EFL League One}}\n{{Premier League}}\n{{EFL Championship}}\n\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1898]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Sport in Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Premier League clubs]]\n[[Category:English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:FA Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:1898 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Companies that have entered administration in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Association football club}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Portsmouth\n| image = Portsmouth FC logo.svg\n| current = 2019\u201320 Portsmouth F.C. season\n| fullname = Portsmouth Football Club\n| nickname = Pompey\n| founded = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1898|04|05}}\n| ground = [[Fratton Park]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|50|47|47|N|1|3|50|W|type:landmark|display=it}}\n| capacity = 20,620 (currently reduced to 19,669 for safety reasons)\n| owner = [[The Tornante Company]]\n| chairman = [[Michael Eisner]]\n| manager = [[Kenny Jackett]]\n| mgrtitle = Manager\n| league = {{English football updater|Portsmou}}\n| season = {{English football updater|Portsmou2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|Portsmou3}}\n| website = http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = _portsmouth1920H\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_sh1 = \n| pattern_so1 = _eng18a\n| leftarm1 = 0000FF\n| body1 = 0000FF\n| rightarm1 = 0000FF\n| shorts1 = FFFFFF\n| socks1 = FF0000\n| pattern_la2 = _bochum1819a\n| pattern_b2 = _bochum1819a\n| pattern_ra2 = _bochum1819a\n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2 = CCCCCC\n| body2 = CCCCCC\n| rightarm2 = CCCCCC\n| shorts2 = CCCCCC\n| socks2 = CCCCCC\n| pattern_la3 = _burgos1819a\n| pattern_b3 = _burgos1819a\n| pattern_ra3 = _burgos1819a\n| pattern_sh3 = _white_stripes\n| pattern_so3 = \n| leftarm3 = 5F04B4\n| body3 = 5F04B4\n| rightarm3 = 5F04B4\n| shorts3 = 5F04B4\n| socks3 = 5F04B4\n}}\n\n'''Portsmouth Football Club''' is an English professional [[association football]] club in [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]], which plays in [[EFL League One]], the third tier of English football. The club was founded on 5 April 1898 and home matches are played at [[Fratton Park]] in [[Milton, Portsmouth]].\n\nPortsmouth have been the top tier [[List of English football champions|Football League Champions of England]] twice consecutively in [[1948\u201349 in English football|1949]] and [[1949\u201350 in English football|1950]]. Portsmouth have also won the [[FA Cup]] twice in [[1939 FA Cup Final|1939]] and [[2008 FA Cup Final|2008]], the [[FA Charity Shield]] once in [[1949 FA Charity Shield|1949]] and the [[2019 EFL Trophy Final|EFL Trophy]] once in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/47379579|title=Relive Portsmouth's Checkatrade Trophy final win|date=27 March 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The [[EFL Cup]] is the only major domestic cup competition that Portsmouth has yet to win.\n\nPortsmouth have also won the second tier division title once in [[2002\u201303 Football League|2002\u201303]], the third tier division title three times in [[1923\u201324 Football League#Third Division South|1923\u201324 (South)]], [[1961\u201362 Football League#Third Division|1961\u201362]], [[1982\u201383 Football League#Third Division|1982\u201383]] and the fourth tier division title once in [[2016\u201317 EFL League Two|2016\u201317]]. In the early twentieth century, Portsmouth were also champions of the [[Southern Football League]] in [[1901\u201302 Southern Football League|1901\u201302]] and [[1919\u201320 Southern Football League|1919\u201320]]. Portsmouth were also champions of the [[Western Football League]] in [[1900\u201301 Western Football League|1900\u201301]], [[1901\u201302 Western Football League|1901\u201302]] and [[1902\u201303 Western Football League|1902\u201303]]. These, and their more recent wins, make Portsmouth southern England\u2019s most successful club (in terms of cups, honours and titles) outside of London.\n\nPortsmouth have played in European competition for only one season in their history, the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Cup]] (now [[UEFA Europa League]]), a result of winning the 2008 FA Cup Final. In this period, the club had international footballers including [[England national football team|England]] players [[Glen Johnson]], [[Jermain Defoe]], [[Peter Crouch]], [[David James (footballer, born 1970)|David James]] and [[Sol Campbell]]. Between 2003 and 2010 the club spent seven consecutive seasons in the [[Premier League]]. The club's fortunes declined in 2010\u201313 when the club entered administration twice and were relegated three times, reaching the fourth tier ([[EFL League Two]]) and their lowest point since the 1979\u201380 season. The club were saved from liquidation after being bought out by the fan-owned [[Pompey Supporters Trust]] (PST).<ref name=\"PST\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-22097965|title=Tears as Portsmouth fans reclaim football club|last=Hemke|first=Claire|publisher=BBC|date=10 April 2013|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Portsmouth FC begin new era as football league starts |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/23527669 |publisher=BBC |date=2 August 2013 |accessdate=6 September 2013 |first=Simon |last=Mundie}}</ref> This made Portsmouth the largest fan-owned football club in England until 3 August 2017, when the PST sold it to [[The Tornante Company]], an investment company owned by former [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] CEO [[Michael Eisner]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-eisners-tornante-talks-buy-english-soccer-club-portsmouth-report-988219|title=Michael Eisner's Tornante in Talks to Buy English Soccer Club Portsmouth (Report)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-02-23}}</ref><ref name=portsmouthfc.co>{{cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2017/august/tornante-company-complete-purchase-of-portsmouth-fc/|title=Tornante Company Complete Purchase Of Portsmouth FC|website=Portsmouth.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last few months of the PST's ownership, Portsmouth were promoted to [[EFL League One]] after winning the fourth tier EFL League Two divisional championship title on 6 May 2017 in the final league game of the [[2016\u201317 Portsmouth F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]]. Portsmouth then became only the fifth English football club to win [[English football league system|all four tiers of current English professional football]] (after [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]], [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] and [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]). In addition, Portsmouth are also one of only two English football clubs to have been champions of five professional divisions including the former regional [[Football League Third Division South]] championship in the [[1923\u201324 Football League#Third Division South|1923\u201324 season]]. Wolverhampton Wanderers also share this distinction, having won all four divisions, plus a [[Football League Third Division North]] title win, coincidentally in the same [[1923\u201324 Football League#Third Division North|1923\u201324]] season as Portsmouth won the respective South division.\n\n==History==\n\n<!--This section is meant to be just a summary. Please do not add too much detail&nbsp;\u2013 the \"History of Portsmouth F.C.\" article is intended for detailed additions-->\n'''{{main|History of Portsmouth F.C.}}'''\n{{For|information on a breakdown of Portsmouth's league and cup history|List of Portsmouth F.C. seasons}}\n\n===Precursor clubs===\n\n* 1883\u20131896 \u2013 '''Portsmouth A.F.C.''' \u2013 Amateur club formed by Portsmouth architect [[A. E. Cogswell|Arthur Cogswell]]. [[Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]] played as a goalkeeper under the pseudonym, \"A.C. Smith\".\n* ?-1891-?? \u2013 '''Portsmouth Town F.C.''' \u2013 An amateur team who almost became Portsmouth's first professional club, but whose efforts failed and led to their disbandment.\n* 1894\u20131899 \u2013 '''Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C.''' (reformed 1900\u20131901) \u2013 A popular amateur army team based at the [[United Services Recreation Ground]] complex at Burnaby Road, Portsmouth. Their supporters were the originators of the ''\"Town Hall Chimes\"'' (later, ''\"The Pompey Chimes\"'') and the team were nicknamed ''\"Pompey\"'' before the professional Portsmouth F.C. were formed in 1898. A \"professionalism\" scandal in 1899 led to their \"retirement\" and a rise in interest of the new Portsmouth F.C.. Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C. briefly reformed for one more season in 1900\u20131901.\n\n===1898\u20131899: Founding of Portsmouth F.C.===\n[[File:PFCHIGHST.jpg|thumb|right|12 High Street, Old Portsmouth]]\nThe club was first founded on 5 April 1898 at 12 High Street, [[Old Portsmouth]] as ''\"The Portsmouth Football and Athletic Company\"'', with John Brickwood as chairman, The company directors were:\n* John Brickwood (1852\u20131932) (owner of Brickwoods Brewery, Portsmouth. Knighted by King Edward VII in 1904. In 1927, he became [[Brickwood baronets|Sir John Brickwood, 1st Baronet Brickwood of Portsmouth]].)\n* Alfred H. Bone (a local architect and surveyor)\n* George Lewin Oliver (founder and headmaster of 'Oliver's Academy', later known as 'Mile End House [[Preparatory school (United Kingdom)|Preparatory School]]', 384\u2013388 (Old) Commercial Road, Landport, Portsmouth)\n* John Peters (a wine importer)\n* Alderman John Edward Pink (a solicitor, employed by John Brickwood).\n* William Wiggington (a government contractor and former [[Royal Engineers]] Warrant Officer)\n\nA [[Blue Plaque]] on the wall of 12 High Street, Old Portsmouth (Alderman John E. Pink's solicitors' office building) commemorates the founding of 5 April 1898.\n\n===1899\u20131920: Southern Football League and Western Football League (1900\u20131909)===\nIn 1899, work began on developing a plot of former agricultural land near Goldsmith Avenue, [[Milton, Portsmouth]] into a new football ground, bought in 1898 from the local Goldsmith farming family. The new football ground was to be named [[Fratton Park]] after the nearby and convenient [[Fratton railway station]], with an adjoining railway goods yard located between the two.\n\n[[Frank Brettell]] was announced as Portsmouth Football Club's first manager-secretary in February 1899,<ref name=royalartillery>{{cite web|url=http://www.diandsaulbooks.co.uk/glory-gunners---the-history-of-royal-artillery-portsmouth-fc-by-kevin-smith-2264-p.asp|title=Glory Gunners \u2013 The History of Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) FC|website=Dian D Saul Books.co.uk}}</ref> he had been secretary-player with the St Domingo Club (now [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]) in Liverpool and helped \"create the organisation which became Everton\".<ref name=\"The News portsmouth\">{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouth.co.uk/sport/football/pompey/how-pompey-were-formed-120-years-today-1-8445296 |title=How Pompey were formed 120 years today |publisher=The News Portsmouth |date=5 April 2018 |author=Neil Allen |accessdate=5 April 2018 }}</ref> Brettell joined Portsmouth F.C. in May 1899 and his first Portsmouth signings were Irish goalkeeper [[Matt Reilly (footballer)|Matt Reilly]] and Harry Turner both from the recently \"retired\" Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C. Also joining Portsmouth as a new director was Regimental Sergeant-Major Frederick Windrum, the treasurer-trainer from Royal Artillery.<ref name=royalartillery/>\n\nBrettell, with his valuable northern contacts, also signed Scottish footballer [[Tom Wilkie]], the former [[Heart Of Midlothian F.C.|Heart Of Midlothian]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] player. [[Bob Blyth]] and [[Sandy Brown (footballer, born 1877)|Alex \"Sandy\" Brown]] were both signed from [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]. Edward Turner, [[Harold Clarke (footballer)|Harold Clarke]] and Harold Stringfellow all came from Everton. [[Dan Cunliffe]], [[Thomas Cleghorn|Thomas \"Tommy\" Cleghorn]] and [[Bobby Marshall (footballer, born 1876)|Robert \"Bobby\" Marshall]] were all signed from Liverpool.<ref name=\"The News portsmouth\" />\n\nA bold and ambitious application for Portsmouth's direct entry into the Southern League First Division, without the usual probationary period in the lower divisions, was accepted,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.portsmouth.gov.uk/ext/.../dev-redevfrattonprkpompeyvillapplication.pdf |title=Portsmouth application |publisher=portsmouth.gov.uk |url-status=dead}}</ref> and the club joined the [[1899\u20131900 Southern Football League#Division One|Southern Football League Division One]] for the 1899\u20131900 season. The Southern League were very keen to see a professional team from Portsmouth join the Southern League, the Southern League secretary, Mr Nat Whittaker was quoted in the press as saying; \"Personally, I think there is a great future for 'socker'(sic) generally in Portsmouth and if they can only do well next season the success of the club is assured. Help them? Of course, I will, and anyone else who wants to make football grow in the south\". Whittaker also said he was confident that Portsmouth would be elected into the league by the other clubs at the next general meeting of the Southern League, which they were.<ref name=royalartillery/>\n\nPortsmouth's first competitive Southern League match was played away at [[Chatham Town F.C.|Chatham Town]] at Maidstone Road, Chatham on Saturday 2 September 1899,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talkfootball.co.uk/guides/footballclubs/history_of_portsmouth.html|title=Portsmouth FC History|accessdate=4 July 2008|publisher=Talk Football|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531064149/http://www.talkfootball.co.uk/guides/footballclubs/history_of_portsmouth.html|archivedate=31 May 2010}}</ref> which Portsmouth won  1\u20130, with Portsmouth's first-ever goal scored by Harold Clarke. During the match, Portsmouth manager Frank Brettel had sent telegrams of the latest score every fifteen minutes to Fratton Park, where crowds had gathered to hear the latest news.<ref>https://twitter.com/PompeyHistory/status/1168623952215851008</ref> Four days later, on Wednesday 6 September 1899, the first-ever home match at Fratton Park was played; a friendly against local town rivals [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], which Portsmouth won 2\u20130, with goals from Dan Cunliffe and Harold Clarke.<ref>{{cite book | author=Dave Juson & others | title=Saints v Pompey \u2013 A history of unrelenting rivalry| publisher=Hagiology Publishing| year=2004| isbn=0-9534474-5-6 |page=9}}</ref> Portsmouth's first competitive Southern League home match followed on Saturday 9 September, a 2-0 win against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], with goals again scored by Clarke and Cunliffe, attended by a crowd of up to 7000 supporters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pompeyvoices.co.uk/story/28f47e33aa |title=Southern League: Portsmouth 2-0 Reading |work=Pompey Voices |date=9 September 1899 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Portsmouth's first 1899\u20131900 season in the Southern Football League Division One was successful, with the club winning 20 out of 28 league matches, earning them the runner-up spot in the table behind champions, [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].\n\nIn their second [[1900\u201301 Southern Football League#Division One|1900\u201301 Southern Football League Division One]] season, Portsmouth finished in third place behind second place [[Bristol City]] and first place Southampton. Portsmouth also joined the [[1900\u201301 Western Football League]] and finished top as Division One champions.<ref name=\"fchd.info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fchd.info/PORTSMOU.HTM |title=Portsmouth |publisher=Football Club History Database |accessdate=1 July 2018 }}</ref> Also in 1900, Portsmouth chairman John Brickwood had [[A. E. Cogswell|Arthur Cogswell]] design and build another Brickwood's Brewery pub, this one next to Fratton Park at 44 Frogmore Road, and named it ''\"The Pompey\"''.\n\nThe following 1901\u201302 season saw Portsmouth player [[Bob Blyth]] become Portsmouth's second manager on 1 August 1901, replacing Frank Brettell who had left on 31 May 1901. Portsmouth won the [[1901\u201302 Southern Football League]] championship title. However, Portsmouth were not promoted and no teams were relegated. No clubs had applied for election to the Football League proper. In the [[1901\u201302 Western Football League]], Portsmouth also won the Division One championship for a second consecutive season.<ref name=\"fchd.info\"/>\n\nIn the [[1902\u201303 Southern Football League]], Portsmouth finished in third place. In the [[1902\u201303 Western Football League]], Portsmouth won the Division One championship for a third consecutive season.<ref name=\"fchd.info\"/>\n\nThe following [[1903\u201304 Southern Football League]] saw a fourth-place finish. On 5 July 1904, Portsmouth F.C. Chairman and Brickwoods Brewery owner, Sir John Brickwood was [[Knighted]] by His Majesty, [[Edward VII|King Edward VII.]]<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27695/page/4448 |title=The London Gazette 12 July 1904 |publisher=The Gazette archive |date=12 July 1904 |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> In the [[1903\u201304 Western Football League]], Portsmouth finished in fourth position behind champions Tottenham Hotspur.\n\n[[Richard Bonney (footballer)|Richard Bonney]], the ex-army soldier who had co-founded Royal Artillery (Portsmouth) F.C. in 1894, became Portsmouth's third manager on 1 August 1905 for the [[1905\u201306 Southern Football League]]. Portsmouth finished in third place. In the [[1905\u201306 Western Football League]], Portsmouth finished in seventh position behind champions [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]. A new club pavilion was designed and built by Arthur Cogswell in the south-west corner of Fratton Park, which housed the club offices and player's changing rooms. John Brickwood also donated a clock tower spire to the east side of the new pavilion.\n\nIn the [[1906\u201307 Southern Football League]], Portsmouth ended the season as runners-up for a second time, after Fulham won the title by just two points. Meanwhile, in the [[1906\u201307 Western Football League]], the top Division One was split into equal 'A' and 'B' sections, with a playoff between the two section winners to decide a Division One champion. Portsmouth finished in third position in the 'B' section of Division One. The [[1906\u201307 in English football|1906\u201307 season]] was highlighted by the visit of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] to Fratton Park in the [[FA Cup]], which generated a record attendance of 24,329. A 2\u20132 draw meant a replay in [[Manchester]], where Portsmouth recorded a famous 2\u20131 win.\n\nThe next [[1908\u201309 Southern Football League|1908\u201309 season]], Portsmouth finished in fourth position.  In their last [[1908\u201309 Western Football League]] appearance, Portsmouth finished in fourth position of the 'B' section of Division One. At the end of the season, all fourteen members of the split 'A' and 'B' sections of Division One resigned from the Western Football League.\n\nFor the [[1909\u201310 Southern Football League]], Portsmouth abandoned their salmon pink and maroon \"Shrimps\" era shirts and changed their colours to white shirts, navy blue shorts and navy blue socks. Portsmouth ended their season in sixth place.\n\nPortsmouth had a disastrous [[1910\u201311 Southern Football League]] season, winning only 8 of their 38 games and were relegated. Manager Richard Bonney was then let go. A severe financial crisis struck between seasons and a public appeal for funds in May 1911 kept the club afloat.<ref name=\"welcometoportsmouth\">{{cite web |url=http://www.welcometoportsmouth.co.uk/portsmouth%20football%20club.html |title=Portsmouth FC History |publisher=welcometoportsmouth.co.uk |accessdate=2 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n====1912: Reformation====\nWith the recruitment of [[Robert Brown (football manager)|Robert Brown]] from [[Sheffield Wednesday]], as Portsmouth's fourth manager, the team finished second place in the [[1911\u201312 Southern Football League]] Division Two behind [[Merthyr Town]] and were promoted as runners-up. However, the club's finances were in trouble again, with losses and debts increasing to \u00a310,000.<ref name=\"welcometoportsmouth\"/> A shareholders meeting was called on 8 May 1912, where [[George Lewin Oliver]], one of the original founders and directors, proposed that \"''The Portsmouth Football and Athletic Company''\" should be wound up and replaced with a more business orientated company. The original company was then liquidated to remove the debt and on 27 July 1912, the \"''Portsmouth Football Club Ltd''\" was formed as the new parent company of Portsmouth F.C., with substantial financial guarantees given by the board of directors. The original 1898 founding director George Lewin Oliver became the new Portsmouth F.C. chairman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pompeychimes.webs.com/history1898to1939.htm |title=Portsmouth Football Club History |work=The Pompey Chimes |accessdate=23 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor the new [[1912\u201313 Southern Football League]] season back in Division One, Portsmouth, now under new ownership, wore new home colours of blue shirts, white shorts and black stockings.<ref name=\"historicalkits.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Portsmouth/Portsmouth.htm|title=Portsmouth|publisher=Historical Football Kits |accessdate=2 July 2018}}</ref> Portsmouth finished the season in 11th position.\n\nPortsmouth's famous crest, consisting of a crescent moon and star made its first appearance in the [[1913\u201314 Southern Football League|1913\u201314 season]]. The moon and star motif comes from the Portsmouth town (then) coat of arms and are believed to date back as far as the time of Richard I. Curiously, the star on the original badge featured a star with five points rather than the eight that appear on the town crest.<ref name=\"historicalkits.co.uk\"/> Portsmouth ended the season in 9th position.\n\nFootball was suspended during the 1914\u20131918 First World War. Many with connections to Portsmouth F.C. joined the \"Pompey Pals Battalions\", which formed parts of the [[Hampshire Regiment]]. Many never returned home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pompeypals.org.uk/|title=Who were the Pompey Pals |publisher=Pompey Pal Project |accessdate=2 July 2018}}</ref> In 1915, the Fratton End terrace was upgraded to accommodate 8,000 standing supporters and covered with a roof for the first time.<ref name=\"Pompey History Society post\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PompeyHistory/status/1004415665120440322 |publisher=Pompey History Society |date=6 June 2018 |accessdate=2 July 2018 |website=Twitter.com |title=Baseball match}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dalyhistory.wordpress.com/2012/02/27/the-history-of-fratton-park/|title=The History of Fratton Park|date=27 February 2012|publisher=}}</ref> On 6 June 1918, an American army team played a Canadian army team in a baseball match at Fratton Park, with the gate money donated to the British Red Cross. The US army team won 4\u20133.<ref name=\"Pompey History Society post\"/><ref name=\"welcometoportsmouth\"/>\n\nFollowing the resumption of matches in the [[1919\u201320 Southern Football League|1919\u201320 season]], Portsmouth won the Southern League championship for the second time (the first occasion being in 1901\u201302). Portsmouth were then elected to the Football League Third Division as founder members. [[John McCartney (footballer, born 1866)|John McCartney]] took over as the fifth manager of Portsmouth on 1 May 1920 from Robert Brown who had left to join [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], also in The Football League.\n\n[[File:PortsmouthFC League Performance.svg|thumb|right|Chart of table positions for Portsmouth since joining the Football League.]]\n\n===1920\u20131939: The Football League===\nSouthern Football League champions Portsmouth coincidentally began the inaugural [[1920\u201321 Football League#Third Division|1920\u201321 season]] in England's [[Football League Third Division]] as founder members and finished 12th that year.\n\nThe following 1921\u201322 season, Football League Third Division was split into North and South sections (which continued until 1958).  The Third Division South was mainly the continuation of the Third Division of the previous 1920\u201321 season, while most of the teams in Third Division North were newcomers to the Football League. Portsmouth finished third in the [[1921\u201322 Football League|1921\u201322 Third Division South]] season.\n\nPortsmouth won the Third Division South title in the [[1923\u201324 Football League Third Division South|1923\u201324 season]] and were promoted to the Football League Second Division.\n\nPortsmouth's debut season in the [[1924\u201325 Football League#Second Division|1924\u201325 Second Division season]] was a successful one, finishing in fourth place behind [[Derby County]], Manchester United and the division champions, [[Leicester City]].\n\nAt the beginning of the [[1925\u201326 Football League#Second Division|1925\u201326 Second Division season]], a new South Stand was designed by renowned football architect [[Archibald Leitch]] and was opened by Football League President John McKenna on 29 August 1925, just before the kickoff against Middlesbrough.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pompeyvoices.co.uk/story/0ff8ec6ee5 |title=The Open of the New South Stand (29 August 1925)|publisher=PompeyVoices |accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> The season ended with Portsmouth in eleventh position.\n\nThe club continued to perform well in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]], winning promotion to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] by finishing runners-up in the [[1926\u201327 in English football|1926\u201327 Second Division season]], gaining a new club record 9\u20131 Fratton Park home win over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] along the way, which is still the highest home win scoring record to date. Portsmouth's promotion to the top division in English football was a double celebration; the first achieved by a football club based south of London, and the first achieved by a club graduating from the Third Division to the First Division.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/PompeyHistory/status/993467779616530432 |title=The promotion to the first division in 1927 |publisher=Pompey History Society |date=7 May 2018 |accessdate=5 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Sunderland A.F.C.]] fan and  [[Gateshead A.F.C.|South Shields]] manager [[Jack Tinn]] joined Portsmouth as new manager on 1 May 1927, replacing John McCartney who had resigned due to ill health.  Portsmouth's debut season in the [[1927\u201328 Football League|1927\u201328 First Division]] was a struggle, finishing one point and one place above relegation.\n\nThe next 1928\u201329 season in the First Division, Portsmouth continued to falter, losing 10\u20130 away at [[Filbert Street]] to Leicester City, which is still a club record away defeat. Despite their failings in the Football League, however, that season also saw Portsmouth reach the [[1929 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]] for the first time, which they lost to [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]. One Pompey supporter is reported to have \"carried a black cat, with the club colours around its neck\" to the 1929 FA Cup Final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pompeyvoices.co.uk/story/7f76d0a19d |title=Key Match: 1929 FA Cup Final |publisher=Pompey Voices |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> Portsmouth managed to survive relegation, finishing one place above relegation.\n\nFrom 1929 to 1934, Portsmouth had become a regular top-half table finisher in the First Division. The [[1933\u201334 in English football|1933\u201334 season]] saw Portsmouth again reach the FA Cup final for a second time, having beaten Manchester United, Bolton Wanderers, Leicester City and [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on the way. The club was again defeated in the [[1934 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]], this time by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].\n\nHalfway through the 1934\u201335 season, on 23 December 1934, the original 1898 founding director and later Portsmouth chairman, George Lewin Oliver died.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/34163/page/3409/data.pdf |title=George Lewin Oliver Obituary |publisher=The London Gazette |date=24 May 1935 |accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> Using money from the June 1934 sale of defender [[Jimmy Allen (footballer, born 1909)|Jimmy Allen]] and money from the 1934 FA Cup Final, Portsmouth F.C. announced at Christmas 1934 that Fratton Park's North Stand was to be demolished and replaced with a much larger stand, increasing the ground capacity to more than 58,000.<ref name=\"northstand\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pompeyvoices.co.uk/story/d77e243589 |title=The New North Stand (7 September 1935) |publisher=PompeyVoices |accessdate=24 May 2018 }}</ref> The [[1934\u201335 Football League#First Division|1934\u201335 season]] ended with Portsmouth in fourteenth position and seven points above relegation.\n\nOn 7 September at the beginning of the [[1935\u201336 Football League#First Division|1935\u201336 First Division season]], in a home game against [[Aston Villa]], the new North Stand was opened by John McKenna, who had also opened Fratton Park's new South Stand ten years earlier.<ref name=\"northstand\" /> Former Portsmouth defender Jimmy Allen, whose sale in 1934 had largely paid for the new North Stand, was present at the game, as captain of the visiting Aston Villa team. The new North Stand briefly held the nickname of \"The Jimmy Allen Stand\" for a while afterwards. Portsmouth ended the 1935\u201336 season in tenth place.\n\n===1938\u201339 season: First FA Cup triumph===\nHaving established themselves in the top flight, the [[1938\u201339 in English football|1938\u201339 season]] saw Portsmouth reach the [[1939 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]] for the third time with manager Jack Tinn, who had worn his 'lucky' [[spats (footwear)|spats]] throughout the qualifying rounds. This was indeed third time lucky, as Portsmouth managed to defeat favourites [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] 4\u20131 in what the press had dubbed, 'The Gland Final' \u2013 a reference to 'monkey gland' [[Testosterone (medication)|testosterone injections]] \u2013 used by both teams (and others) that season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesefootballtimes.co/2015/08/05/monkey-glands-and-the-major/|title=Monkey Glands and the Major|publisher=These Football Times |accessdate=5 July 2018 |first=Connor |last=Heffernan |date=8 May 2015}}</ref> [[Bert Barlow]] and [[John Anderson (footballer, born 1915)|John 'Jock' Anderson]] scored, whilst [[Cliff Parker (footballer)|Cliff Parker]] scored twice (third and fourth goals).\n\nThe new [[1939\u201340 in English football|1939\u201340 season]] in the First Division began on Saturday 26 August 1939.  On Friday 1 September 1939, Germany invaded Poland. On Saturday 2 September 1939, all divisions of the Football League played their third and final game of the season, with [[Blackpool F.C.]] at the top of the table and Portsmouth in 18th position. These would be the last national Football League fixtures before abandonment following the [[United Kingdom declaration of war on Germany (1939)|British declaration of war on Germany]] on Sunday 3 September 1939. Large gatherings of crowds were suspended with the implementation of the [[Emergency Powers (Defence) Act 1939]].\n\nHowever, football competitions did take place during the war, with the Football League being split into ten regional mini leagues, with Portsmouth in [[1939\u201340 in English football|'League South']]. An annual national cup competition was held too, called the [[Football League War Cup]].\n\nIn 1942, Portsmouth reached the [[London War Cup]] final,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pompeyvoices.co.uk/story/b0bdf8dc47 |title=1942 London War Cup Final |publisher=Pompey Voices |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> a competition that had begun only a season earlier in 1940\u201341. The London War Cup was held once again during the 1941\u201342 season and was intended by its organisers to stand in for the FA Cup, despite the official Football League War Cup competition had been taking place annually since 1939.  The London War Cup competition required Portsmouth, the current FA Cup champions, to secede from the Football Association to enter. Portsmouth progressed to the 1942 London War Cup final at Wembley Stadium, but were beaten by [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and finished as runners-up. After the competition, Portsmouth paid a ten Pounds readmission fee to rejoin the Football Association again.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoateallthepies.tv/chelsea/209868/70-years-of-hurt-brentford-fans-launch-petition-asking-chelsea-to-return-the-london-wartime-cup-they-won-in-1942.html |title=70 Years of Hurt:Brentford fans launch petition asking Chelsea to return the London Wartime Cup they won in 1942 |publisher=Who Ate All the Pies |first=Chris |last=Wright |date=17 March 2015 |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> The London War Cup competition was never played again. Ironically, the London War Cup trophy won by Brentford in 1942 was reused for subsequent Football League War Cup competitions. The trophy was last presented in 1945 to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and remains in the Chelsea F.C. museum today.\n\nDuring his wartime visits to Portsmouth, [[Field Marshal Montgomery]] became interested in Portsmouth Football Club and was made honorary President of Portsmouth F.C. in 1944 (until 1961).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/news/pompey-mentioned-in-monty-s-despatches-1-1261833|title=Pompey mentioned in Monty's despatches|publisher=Portsmouth News |date=15 June 2004 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe end of World War II in 1945 caused Portsmouth to hold the distinction of holding the FA Cup trophy for the longest uninterrupted period of seven years, as the trophy was not presented again until the 1946 FA Cup Final. Manager Jack Tinn was rumoured to have kept the FA Cup trophy 'safe under his bed' during a part of the war. Because the navy city of Portsmouth was a primary strategic military target for German Luftwaffe bombing, the FA Cup trophy was routinely moved around the city of Portsmouth for its safety and protection, moving from Fratton Park's boardroom, into bank vaults, back to Fratton Park and around local pubs. During the worst of the bombing on Portsmouth, the FA Cup trophy was also taken ten miles north of Portsmouth, to the nearby Hampshire village of [[Lovedean]], where it was kept and displayed in a quaint thatched roof country pub called \"The Bird in Hand\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lovedeanbirdinhand.co.uk/?BIHrequestID=4C55838218D9D39854D199BD64BA29 |title=About Us |publisher=The Bird in Hand |website=lovedeanbirdinhand.co.uk |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> In 1945, the FA Cup trophy was taken around the streets of Portsmouth and proudly shown off at [[Victory in Europe Day]] street parties.\n\nFA Cup competition was resumed for the [[1945\u201346 in English football|1945\u201346 season]], but the resumption of the Football League had to wait one more year. Portsmouth, as a Division One team and as the current FA Cup Champions (from 1939), were drawn to play against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in the Third Round stage of the FA Cup competition. The first of the two-leg tie was played at Birmingham's [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St. Andrew's]] stadium on 5 January 1946 and the result was 1\u20130 in Birmingham City's favour. The second leg at Fratton Park ended 0\u20130 on 9 January 1946, with Birmingham City winning 1\u20130 overall on aggregate. (See [[1945\u201346 FA Cup]] for full results) Sadly, the FA Cup trophy was not to stay with Portsmouth for an eighth consecutive year and was returned to the Football Association in time for the [[1946 FA Cup Final]], in which Derby County were awarded the trophy.\n\nThe Football League finally resumed in [[1946\u201347 Football League|1946\u201347]]. Portsmouth had capitalised on the footballers called up to serve in the Royal Navy and Royal Marines in the war years and recruited some of them. In this way, Portsmouth had the pick of some of the best. Portsmouth ended the 1946\u201347 Football League First Division season in 12th place. On 1 May 1947, legendary manager Jack Tinn left Portsmouth, with [[Bob Jackson (football manager)|Bob Jackson]] taking over the role on the same day.\n\nThe second post-war Football League First Division season resumed under manager Bob Jackson in [[1947\u201348 Football League|1947\u201348]]. This was also the first season Portsmouth wore red socks, which replaced their traditional black socks. The red socks were an idea proposed by Portsmouth's honorary president, Field Marshal Montgomery, who had suggested that Portsmouth should wear red socks to commemorate the sacrifice of British servicemen lost in war. Red is traditionally the colour of the [[British Army]] and also of the [[Remembrance poppy]] flower, and so Montgomery's idea was adopted by Portsmouth at the start of the season. Bob Jackson's Portsmouth finished in 8th place at the end of the [[1947\u201348 Football League|1947\u201348 First Division season]].\n\n===1948\u201349 and 1949\u201350: Champions of England===\nIn their 50-year \"Golden Jubilee\" anniversary [[1948\u201349 Football League|1948\u201349 season]], Bob Jackson's Portsmouth side were tipped to be the first team of the 20th century to win a historic Football League and FA Cup \"[[Double (association football)|double]]\".  The potential of a rare 'Double' saw Fratton Park attracting average home attendances of 36,000 supporters, and a record attendance of 51,385 in an FA Cup quarter-final match against Derby County on 26 February 1949, which Portsmouth won 2\u20131. The Fratton Park attendance of 51,385 is no longer a club record. Portsmouth lost 1\u20133 in the FA Cup semi-final against Leicester City on 26 March 1949 at the neutral [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] stadium. Portsmouth however, did win one half of the 'Double', securing the First Division title and becoming Football League Champions of England at the end of the [[1948\u201349 Portsmouth F.C. season|1948\u201349 season]], with Manchester United finishing as runners-up. Portsmouth's championship-winning team consisted of [[Ernest Butler]], [[Phil Rookes]], [[Harry Ferrier]], [[Jimmy Scoular]], [[Reg Flewin]], [[Jimmy Dickinson]], [[Peter Harris (footballer)|Peter Harris]], [[Duggie Reid]], [[Ike Clarke]], [[Len Phillips]], [[Jack Froggatt]], [[Jasper Yeuell]], [[Lindy Delapenha]], [[Bert Barlow]] and [[Cliff Parker (footballer)|Cliff Parker]].\n\nBob Jackson's Portsmouth side beat [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 5\u20131 on the last day of the following [[1949\u201350 Football League|1949\u201350 season]], winning the Football League title again for a second consecutive season \u2013 on goal difference \u2013 as both Portsmouth and runners up [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]] finished the season with 53 points each, and only one point ahead of third place Sunderland on 52 points. Portsmouth are one of only five English teams to have won back-to-back consecutive top-flight League titles since the end of World War II.\n\nIn the following [[1950\u201351 Football League#First Division|1950\u201351 season]], League champions Portsmouth finished in 7th position, 13 points behind title winners Tottenham Hotspur.\n\n[[Eddie Lever]] took over at Pompey in 1952 after championship-winning manager Bob Jackson joined [[Hull City]]. In the [[1952\u201353 Football League#First Division|1952\u201353 season]], Portsmouth finished in 15th place and only 4 points above the relegation zone, with [[Arsenal F.C.]] winning the league title.\n\nPortsmouth finished third in the [[1954\u201355 Football League#First Division|1954\u201355 season]], only 4 points behind winners [[Chelsea F.C.]].\n\nIn the [[1955\u201356 Football League#First Division|1955\u201356 season]], on 22 February 1956, Fratton Park hosted the Football League's first ever floodlit evening game, against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], played under floodlights erected on top of the North Stand and South Stand roofs.<ref>{{harvnb|Inglis|1996|p=295}}</ref><ref>OUR ASSOCIATION FOOTBALL CORRESPONDENT. \"League Game By Floodlight.\" Times [London, England] 23 February 1956: 13. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 3 December 2013.</ref> Portsmouth ended the season in 12th place in Division One.\n\nThe original solid earthbank Fratton End stand was replaced in 1956 with a new stand built from prefabricated concrete and steel. It had two distinctive terraced tiers, a roofed upper terrace and an open-air lower terrace. In the [[1956\u201357 Football League#First Division|1956\u201357 season]], Portsmouth escaped relegation by four points and finished two places above the drop zone.\n\nIn the following [[1957\u201358 Football League#First Division|1957\u201358 season]], Portsmouth once again escaped relegation on goal difference and finished one place above the relegation zone. Manager Eddie Lever left Portsmouth in April 1958.\n\n[[Freddie Cox]] became new Portsmouth manager in August 1958. The new 1958\u201359 season was the first Football League season with four national divisions. The two old regional Third Divisions (North and South) which had begun in the 1921\u201322 season were restructured and replaced with two new national divisions, named the Third Division and Fourth Division. At the end of the [[1958\u201359 Football League|1958\u201359 season]] Portsmouth finished bottom of the First Division, ending their 32-year stay in the First Division, and relegation to the Second Division. By now, the championship winning team of 1949 and 1950 had been broken up, caused by ageing or injury.\n\n===1959\u20131979: Decline and relegation to the Fourth Division===\nFollowing the bottom-place finish in the previous 1958\u201359 First Division season, Portsmouth started the [[1959\u201360 Football League|1959\u201360 season]] in the Second Division, the second tier of English football, which Portsmouth had last been in during the 1926\u201327 season. After another poor season, they escaped a further relegation to the Third Division only by 2 points and finishing only one place above the relegation zone.\n\nIn the [[1960\u201361 Football League|1960\u201361 season]] Portsmouth finished second-to-last place in the Second Division relegation zone and were relegated once again to the Third Division, (the first former [[English football champions|English League champions]] to do so). Manager [[Freddie Cox]] was sacked in February 1961.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blog.woolwicharsenal.co.uk/archives/6642 |title=Freddie Cox DFC |publisher=AISA Arsenal History Society |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnder the guidance of [[George Smith (footballer, born 1915)|George Smith]], Portsmouth, now in the Third Division for the [[1961\u201362 Football League First Division|1960\u201361 season]] had a good season and were promoted back to the Second Division at the first time of asking after winning the Third Division title. Field-Marshal Bernard 'Monty' Montgomery of Alamein, was the honorary President of Portsmouth, having begun to support them during World War II due to the proximity of his headquarters at [[Southwick House]] on the outskirts of Portsmouth. In private correspondence dated 25 April 1962, he wrote to Smith: \"I congratulate you very much on getting Portsmouth out of the Third Division \u2013 which was completely a wrong place for a famous team. While the players all did their stuff, the major credit goes to you.\"\n\nDespite limited financial means, manager George Smith maintained Portsmouth's Second Division status throughout the rest of the 1960s until Smith was replaced by [[Ron Tindall]] in April 1970 as Smith moved upstairs to become general manager in April 1970, until his retirement from football in 1973.\n\nThe cash injection that accompanied the arrival of John Deacon as chairman in 1972 failed to improve Portsmouth's Second Division position. Ron Tindall was replaced in May 1973 by [[John Mortimore (footballer)|John Mortimore]]. However, Ron Tindall returned for two games as caretaker manager after manager John Mortimore left in 1974. [[Ian St. John]] became new Portsmouth manager in September 1974.\n\nWith Deacon unable to continue bankrolling the club on the same scale, Portsmouth finished bottom of the Second Division in the [[1975\u201376 Football League#Second Division|1975\u201376 season]] and were relegated down to the Third Division.\n\nIn November of the [[1976\u201377 Football League|1976\u201377 Third Division season]], the club found itself needing to raise [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]25,000 to pay off debts and so avoid bankruptcy.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} With players having to be sold to ease the club's financial situation, and no money available for replacements, Portsmouth were forced to rely on inexperienced young players. Initially results improved, but then declined again. On 4 May 1977, Ian St. John was replaced as manager by former Portsmouth and England international player [[Jimmy Dickinson]]. They ended the [[1976\u201377 Football League|1976\u201377 season]] only one place and one point above the Third Division's relegation zone.\nThey were relegated at the end of the new 1977\u201378 season, finishing in bottom place.\n\nIn the [[1978\u201379 Football League|1978\u201379 Fourth Division season]], Portsmouth finished in 7th position. Jimmy Dickinson suffered a heart attack near the end of the season and after the season in May 1979, was replaced by [[Frank Burrows]].\n\n===1979\u20131987: Return to the First Division===\nUnder Frank Burrows new management, Portsmouth gained promotion back to the Third Division after finishing in 4th place in the [[1979\u201380 Football League#Fourth Division|1979\u201380 season]].\n\nThe following [[1981\u201382 Football League#Third Division|1981\u201382 Third Division season]], Portsmouth finished mid-table in thirteenth position. On 21 May 1982, Frank Burrows departed and [[Bobby Campbell (English footballer)|Bobby Campbell]] became the new Portsmouth manager.\n\nDuring the [[1982\u201383 Football League#Third Division|1982\u201383 Third Division season]], former Portsmouth player, manager and England international [[Jimmy Dickinson]] died aged 57 on 8 November 1982 after suffering three heart attacks. A public memorial service was held at a packed [[St Mary's Church, Portsea|St. Mary's Church]] in Fratton, Portsmouth.  Dickinson was laid to rest in [[Alton, Hampshire]]. Pompey later that season won the [[1982\u201383 Football League#Third Division|1982\u201383 Third Division championship title]], gaining promotion back to the Second Division.\n\nIn the [[1983\u201384 Football League#Second Division|1983\u201384 Second Division season]], Portsmouth finished sixteenth place in the table. After the season, Bobby Campbell was replaced by former England international and [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] winner, [[Alan Ball Jr.|Alan Ball]] on 11 May 1984.\n\nUnder Ball, Portsmouth's results markedly improved and they narrowly missed winning promotion to the First Division in the [[1984\u201385 Football League#Second Division|1984\u201385 Second Division season]], finishing in 4th place on goal difference. They finished in 4th place again for the following [[1985\u201386 Football League#Second Division|1985\u201386 season]].\n\nIn Ball's third season as Portsmouth manager in the [[1986\u201387 Football League#Second Division|1986\u201387 Second Division season]], Portsmouth finished as runners-up behind Derby County, gaining promotion back to the First Division for the first time since the 1958\u201359 season. During the season, the upper tier of the Fratton End stand, built only thirty years earlier in 1956, was closed due to structural concerns, leaving only the lower tier of the Fratton End open to fans.\n\nBy the middle of the new [[1987\u201388 Football League#First Division|1987\u201388 First Division season]], the club was again in financial trouble. Portsmouth were relegated straight back down to the Second Division. The summer of 1988 saw chairman John Deacon sell the club to London-based businessman and former [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] chairman, [[Jim Gregory (football chairman)|Jim Gregory]].  Fratton Park was in a poor condition, with the Fratton End still half closed to fans and leaking roofs in the North and South stands.\n\nWith new chairman Jim Gregory injecting money into the club, work began in the summer of 1988 to demolish the upper tier of the Fratton End and its roof. The North and South stands were refurbished and both received smart new blue-coloured metal sheet roofs.\n\n===1988\u20132003: The Second Tier===\n\nAfter a single disappointing season in the First Division, Portsmouth were relegated back to the Second Division for the [[1988\u201389 Football League#Second Division|1988\u201389 season]]. Halfway through the season, Alan Ball was sacked on 17 January 1989 and replaced by [[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]]. The entire Fratton End stand was closed during most of the season during demolition works, with only the lower tier of the stand reopening in the springtime of 1989. Portsmouth ended the season only two places above the relegation zone.\n\nFollowing the 15 April 1989 [[Hillsborough Disaster]], Portsmouth removed the perimeter fences from Fratton Park for the new [[1989\u201390 Football League#Second Division|1989\u201390 season]], except at the Milton End to separate away supporters.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} The season saw John Gregory leaving the club on 3 January 1990. Assistant manager Frank Burrows became manager for a second spell on 23 January 1990. Portsmouth finished in 12th position at the end of the season.\n\nThe [[1990\u201391 Football League#Second Division|1990\u201391 season]] saw Frank Burrows resign as manager on 13 March 1991 after a string of bad results. Burrows was replaced by coach [[Graham Paddon]] until the end of the season, finishing in 17th position.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n[[Jim Smith (footballer, born 1940)|Jim Smith]]'s arrival as manager at the start of the [[1991\u201392 Portsmouth F.C. season|1991\u201392 season]] sparked a revival in the team's fortunes and that year Portsmouth reached the semi-finals of the [[1991\u201392 FA Cup|FA Cup]], meeting Liverpool at neutral ground Highbury on 5 April 1992 \u2013 the 94th Anniversary of Portsmouth Football Club. Portsmouth took the lead in extra time from a 111th minute [[Darren Anderton]] goal. However, Liverpool's [[Ronnie Whelan]] equalised five minutes later, and the semi-final match ended tied 1\u20131 after the allotted 120 minutes. The tie was then replayed at [[Villa Park]] on 13 April 1992 and ended 0\u20130 after extra time.  Portsmouth then lost 1\u20133 on penalties to Liverpool, who went on to meet Sunderland in the 1992 FA Cup Final, which Liverpool won 2\u20130.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe [[1992\u201393 Football League]] season saw a major restructuring of the [[English football league system|English football \"pyramid\" system]], caused by all the First Division clubs resigning from the Football League and forming a new breakaway top tier [[FA Premier League]]. Now without a First Division, the Football League Second Division was renamed as the [[1992\u201393 Football League#First Division|\"Football League First Division\"]] for the 1992\u201393 season. The FA Premier League also had a new winners trophy made, meaning the famous old Football League First Division championship trophy became demoted in status, now acting as the new second tier \"First Division\" championship trophy instead. Portsmouth had a good 1992\u201393 season in the new \"First Division\", but missed out on automatic promotion to the new first tier Premier League by virtue of scoring only one fewer goal than second-placed [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. In the subsequent promotion play-offs, Portsmouth lost 3\u20132 on aggregate over two games to Leicester City in the play-off semi-finals for the third promotion place.\n\nDuring the [[1993\u201394 Portsmouth F.C. season|1993\u201394 season]] under manager Jim Smith, Portsmouth finished 17th out of 24 in the First Division, winning 15 matches, drawing 13 and losing 18. The team reached the quarterfinals of the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] and the third round of the FA Cup, in both cases being knocked out after replays.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe [[1994\u201395 Portsmouth F.C. season|1994\u201395 season]] was a disappointing one for Portsmouth and after a decline in form which left them struggling at the wrong end of the \"new\" First Division, Jim Smith was sacked on 1 February 1995 and was replaced by [[Terry Fenwick]], who guided them to safety with 4 wins in their final 6 league games.\n\nIn the [[1995\u201396 Portsmouth F.C. season|1995\u201396 season]] Fenwick's first full season in charge of Portsmouth, relegation to the Second Division was avoided on the last day of the season (on goal difference) when Portsmouth won away at [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] while other results went the club's way.\n\nIn the summer of 1996, [[Terry Venables]] arrived at Portsmouth as a consultant. Venables had recently resigned as the England national team manager after the [[UEFA Euro 1996]] competition. Fratton Park was transformed into an all-seat stadium, with new blue plastic seats fitted to the lower North terrace, Milton End, lower South terrace paddocks and also to the remnant of the Fratton End terrace.\n\nIn the [[1996\u201397 Portsmouth F.C. season|1996\u201397]] league campaign, Portsmouth finished just short of the qualifying places for the playoffs for promotion to the Premier League. Terry Venables took over as chairman in February 1997 after buying a 51 per cent controlling share in the club for \u00a31.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/46933.stm|title=Venables quits Portsmouth taking a tidy profit|date=13 January 1998|work=BBC News |accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref> The team enjoyed a run in the [[1996\u201397 FA Cup]] competition, beating FA Premier League side [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on 15 February 1997, but were eventually beaten 1\u20134 by Chelsea F.C. in the quarter-finals at Fratton Park on 9 March 1997.\n\nAt the end of the 1996\u201397 season, the Fratton End was fully demolished in the summer (of 1997) and work began to build a new Fratton End stand. In addition, a new roof extension was built over the lower tier of the North Stand and was completed before the new season started. These new additions to Fratton Park were partly funded by the [[Football Trust]] (now [[The Football Foundation]]).\n\nAt 4.59pm on Friday 31 October 1997, the new \u00a32.2 million Fratton End was officially cleared for its opening, with one minute to spare before a 5 pm deadline. Problems with some misorientated Fratton End rooftop floodlights caused the Fratton End of the pitch to be \"shrouded in gloom on Hallowe'en\", according to the Sky Sports 3 TV commentator, causing some doubt that the live televised Division One game against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] would take place.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} Fortunately, the match referee, [[Paul Danson]] gave the go-ahead for the evening fixture. The game was won 0\u20131 by Swindon Town with an official Fratton Park attendance of only 8,707. As a mark of respect to the club's former player and manager, a memorial portrait of [[Jimmy Dickinson]] was incorporated into the seating of the new Fratton End stand, along with the club's crest. Terry Venables' role as coach of the Australian national team meant he was frequently absent from Portsmouth. Meanwhile, the team's results were poor. Two-thirds of the way through the [[1997\u201398 Portsmouth F.C. season|1997\u201398 season]], he and manager Terry Fenwick left the club, with Portsmouth on the bottom of the table, and Venables selling his shareholding back to Martin Gregory, son of former chairman Jim Gregory. Alan Ball then returned as manager for the second time on 26 January 1998. Relegation to the third tier was avoided on the last day of the season \u2013 by 1 point.\n\nPortsmouth's centenary season, [[1998\u201399 Portsmouth F.C. season|1998\u201399]], saw a financial crisis hit the club, and in December 1998 Portsmouth went into [[Administration (football)|financial administration]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16943651|title=Portsmouth enter administration & are docked 10 points|date=17 February 2012|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref> Serbian-born US businessman [[Milan Mandari\u0107]] saved the club with a takeover deal in May 1999, and the new chairman immediately started investing for the new 1999\u20132000 season.\n\nAlan Ball was sacked on 9 December 1999 during the [[1999\u20132000 Portsmouth F.C. season|1999\u20132000]] season with the club near the bottom of the table. [[Tony Pulis]] took over on 13 January 2000 and steered the club to safety at the end of the season.\n\nIn the [[2000\u201301 Portsmouth F.C. season|2000\u201301 season]], Pulis was put on leave and replaced by Portsmouth player, [[Steve Claridge]] in a player-manager role.  On 23 February 2001, [[Graham Rix]] took over from Claridge. Portsmouth escaped relegation on the last day of the 2000\u201301 season when they won their final game and [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] lost theirs, keeping Portsmouth up at their expense.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3004911/Huddersfield-relegated-as-Palace-and-Portsmouth-win.html|title=Huddersfield relegated as Palace and Portsmouth win|date=6 May 2001|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref> During the summer break, former [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] manager [[Harry Redknapp]] was appointed director of football by Mandaric.\n\nA week before the new season began, 25-year-old Portsmouth goalkeeper [[Aaron Flahavan]] was killed in a car crash near Bournemouth on 5 August 2001. In a mark of respect, Portsmouth retired his number 1 shirt for the season. Portsmouth signed veteran Croatian playmaker [[Robert Prosine\u010dki#Portsmouth|Robert Prosine\u010dki]] on a one-year deal and [[Peter Crouch]] for the start of the [[2001\u201302 Portsmouth F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]. Rix lost his job on 25 March 2002, with Harry Redknapp taking over. Former Portsmouth manager Jim Smith was asked to team up with Redknapp, and while he initially turned the offer down to remain as assistant at [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], he soon arrived at Portsmouth after a change of manager at Coventry saw almost all of the club's coaching staff being dismissed. Peter Crouch scored 19 goals for Portsmouth, but was sold to Aston Villa in March 2002 for \u00a35&nbsp;million.  Portsmouth ended the [[2001\u201302 Portsmouth F.C. season|2001\u201302 Division One season]] in 17th place and 4 points above relegation.\n\nIn the [[2002\u201303 Portsmouth F.C. season|2002\u201303 season]], Portsmouth led the First Division for most of the season, with [[Svetoslav Todorov]] scoring 26 league goals, which made him the First Division's top scorer at the end of the season. Portsmouth finished top as First Division champions on 27 April 2003, six points clear of second-placed Leicester City, gaining promotion (with a game to spare) to the FA Premier League, returning to the top tier of English football after an absence of fifteen seasons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Portsmouth clinch promotion and championship |url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/2003/0427/portsmouth.html |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |date= 27 April 2003 |accessdate=27 August 2007}}</ref> Portsmouth were awarded the Football League First Division Championship trophy for a third time, as the former Football League championship trophy had been demoted in status in 1992\u201393 (because of the creation of the FA Premier League) and had become the second tier trophy. Portsmouth goalkeeper [[Shaka Hislop]], midfielders Matthew Taylor and Paul Merson earned places in the 2002\u201303 Division One [[PFA Team of the Year (2000s)#First Division 4|PFA Team of the Year]] award.\n\n===2003\u20132010: FA Premier League===\nIn Portsmouth's Premiership debut season in 2003\u201304, the \"Harry & Jim\" partnership of Harry Redknapp and Jim Smith resulted in a 13th place final position at the end of the season.\n\nAlmost halfway through the following 2004\u201305 season in the Premiership, Harry Redknapp unexpectedly walked out on Portsmouth on 24 November 2004 after a row with chairman Milan Mandari\u0107 over the appointment of new Director of Football [[Velimir Zajec]] at the club. Shortly afterwards on 8 December 2004, Harry Redknapp was announced by Southampton F.C. chairman [[Rupert Lowe]] as their new manager, with Jim Smith as his assistant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/southampton/4077461.stm |title=Saints name Redknapp as boss |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 December 2004 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> Velimir Zajec then replaced Redknapp as Portsmouth manager, but in April 2005, Zajec was replaced by Frenchman [[Alain Perrin]]. Perrin managed to secure Portsmouth's Premiership status with a few games of the season left, including a [[South Coast Derby]] 4\u20131 win over Harry Redknapp's Southampton side,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4451361.stm |title=Portsmouth 4\u20131 Southampton |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 April 2005 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> who were eventually relegated at the end of the season.\n\nDuring the 2005\u201306 season and after achieving only four wins from a total of 20 games as Portsmouth manager, Alain Perrin was sacked on 24 November 2005, exactly one year to the day since Harry Redknapp left Portsmouth. Harry Redknapp then made a surprise return to manage Portsmouth again after leaving relegated Southampton. In January 2006, Portsmouth were sold by Milan Mandari\u0107 and bought by businessman [[Alexandre Gaydamak]]. New signings included a quartet from Tottenham Hotspur, then record signing [[Benjani Mwaruwari|Benjani]] and [[Argentina national football team|Argentine international]] [[Andr\u00e9s D'Alessandro]] on loan from [[VfL Wolfsburg]]. The club survived their third season in the Premier League one place above the relegation zone in 17th position. With large amounts of money available for Redknapp to make record signings, the club finished the [[2006\u201307 Portsmouth F.C. season|2006\u201307 season]] in the top half of the table for the first time, in ninth position, only one point short of European qualification.\n\n[[File:The FA Cup Trophy in 2008.jpg|thumb|Portsmouth won the [[FA Cup]] for the second time in 2008]]\n[[File:Fullscore.JPG|thumb|The scoreboard at the end of the [[2008 FA Cup Final]], in which Portsmouth beat [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] 1\u20130]]\nThe following [[2007\u201308 Portsmouth F.C. season|2007\u201308 season]] saw Portsmouth finish eighth in the Premier League and reach the [[2008 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]] for the first time since 1939. They eliminated Manchester United at [[Old Trafford]] in the quarter-finals, and on 5 April 2008, Portsmouth beat Championship side [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] 1\u20130 at [[Wembley Stadium]] in the semi-finals, coincidentally the same day that the club celebrated its 110th birthday.\n\nOn 17 May 2008, Portsmouth [[2008 FA Cup Final|played]] [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in the second FA Cup final to be played at the newly rebuilt Wembley Stadium. Portsmouth won 1\u20130, with [[Nwankwo Kanu]] scoring the only goal. It was the second time Portsmouth had won the FA Cup.\n\n[[File:Portsmouth kickoff vs AC Milan.jpg|thumb|International strikers [[Peter Crouch]] and [[Nwankwo Kanu]] kick off for Portsmouth in their [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] match against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]]]\nThe FA Cup win had also earned Portsmouth a place in the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Cup]], the club's first time playing European football. Their first European match was a 2\u20130 victory over [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]] in the first round on 18 September. Portsmouth went on to win the tie 4\u20132 on aggregate, progressing to the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Cup group stage|group stage]]. On 25 October 2008, Redknapp suddenly left Portsmouth for a second time, leaving his assistant [[Tony Adams]] to be promoted to the managerial role. On 27 November 2008, Portsmouth drew 2\u20132 with [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], going 2\u20130 up through goals from [[Youn\u00e8s Kaboul]] and Nwankwo Kanu, but conceding two goals later in the game.  Adams was dismissed in February 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/7878084.stm |title=Portsmouth confirm Adams sacking |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 February 2009 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> Youth team coach [[Paul Hart]] took over as manager until the end of the season, and Portsmouth were guaranteed Premier League safety on 16 May 2009. Portsmouth finished the [[2008\u201309 Premier League]] season in 14th place. On 26 May, Portsmouth accepted a bid from [[United Arab Emirates|Emirati]] businessman [[Sulaiman Al Fahim]] to purchase the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8070535.stm|title=Portsmouth agree to takeover bid |date=27 May 2009|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=27 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nBecause of the financial problems suffered by the club, Portsmouth were forced to sell several of their top players and high earners, including Peter Crouch, [[Sylvain Distin]], [[Glen Johnson]] and [[Niko Kranj\u010dar]]. On 21 July 2009, Al Fahim was appointed non-executive chairman of Portsmouth. On 19 August 2009, Portsmouth announced on their website that a rival consortium headed by current CEO [[Peter Storrie]] had also made a bid for the club; unknown at the time, this was backed by [[Ali al-Faraj]]. Despite this, Al Fahim completed the takeover on 26 August 2009; al Faraj moved to review a takeover of West Ham United.\n\nAs the early stages of the [[2009\u201310 Portsmouth F.C. season|2009\u201310 season]] progressed, the finances dried up and the club admitted on 1 October that some of their players and staff had not been paid. On 3 October, media outlets started to report that a deal was nearing completion for Ali al-Faraj to take control of the club. On 5 October, a deal was agreed for al-Faraj and his associates, via [[British Virgin Islands|BVI]]-registered company Falcondrone, to hold a 90% majority holding, with Al-Fahim retaining 10% stake and the title of non-executive chairman for two years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8222718.stm|title=Al Fahim completes Pompey buy-out|date=26 August 2009|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=26 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/index.php?cms_id=78&qs_articleid=2775&qs_media=html|title=Portsmouth Football Club Statement|publisher=Portsmouth Football Club|date=26 August 2009|accessdate=26 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111225174753/http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/index.php?cms_id=78&qs_articleid=2775&qs_media=html|archivedate=25 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Falcondrone also agreed a deal with Alexandre Gaydamak the right to buy, for \u00a31, Miland Development (2004) Ltd., which owns various strategic pockets of land around the ground, once refinancing was complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=683043&cc=5739|title=Portsmouth's second takeover is confirmed|publisher=ESPN SoccerNet|date=3 October 2009|accessdate=3 October 2009}}</ref> Two days after the al-Faraj takeover was completed, Portsmouth's former technical director [[Avram Grant]] returned as [[director of football]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8295129.stm|title=Grant seals return to Portsmouth |date=7 October 2009|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=9 October 2009}}</ref> Because of the financial problems, however, the Premier League placed the club under a transfer embargo, meaning the club were not allowed to sign any players.\n\nAvram Grant took over at Portsmouth on 26 November 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/News/news/Grant-To-Be-Boss.aspx |title=Grant to be boss |publisher=Portsmouth Football Club |accessdate=26 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129083931/http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/News/news/Grant-To-Be-Boss.aspx |archivedate=29 November 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8378603.stm |publisher=BBC Sport | title=Portsmouth name Grant as new boss | date=26 November 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> replacing Hart, who had been sacked by the board two days previously due to the club's position at the bottom of the league table.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8377374.stm |publisher=BBC Sport | title=Portsmouth part company with Hart | date=24 November 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, it was announced that the club had failed to pay the players for the second consecutive month,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8394092.stm |publisher=BBC Sport | title=Portsmouth loan settles players' wages crisis | date=4 December 2009 | accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref> and on the 31st it was announced player's wages would again be paid late, on 5 January 2010. According to common football contracts, the players then had the right to terminate their contracts and leave the club without any compensation for the club, upon giving two weeks' notice. Despite the financial difficulties, Grant's time as manager was initially successful. He gained two wins (against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and Liverpool) and a draw away at Sunderland from his first five games. The only losses inflicted on Portsmouth in this period were by eventual [[double (association football)|double]] winners [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and the previous season's champions, Manchester United. [[HM Revenue and Customs]] (HMRC) filed a winding-up petition against Portsmouth at the [[High Court of Justice]] in London on 23 December 2009.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8434987.stm |publisher=BBC News | title=Portsmouth FC's 'shock' at HMRC wind-up petition | date=30 December 2009 | accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref> In March 2010, this winding-up petition was dropped,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8570134.stm |publisher=BBC News | title=HMRC drops Portsmouth administration challenge | date=16 March 2010 | accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref> leaving Portsmouth with a nine-point penalty for entering administration.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8571990.stm |publisher=BBC Sport | title=Portsmouth deducted nine points | date=17 March 2010 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Administration, 2010 FA Cup Final and relegation====\nDuring the 2009\u201310 season, it had become apparent to the club's new owner [[Balram Chainrai]] that Portsmouth were approximately \u00a3135&nbsp;million in debt<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8664722.stm |title= Portsmouth debt goes up to \u00a3135m |publisher=BBC Sport | date=6 May 2010 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> so to protect the club from liquidation, Chainrai placed the club into administration on 26 February 2010, and the club appointed Andrew Andronikou, Peter Kubik and Michael Kiely of accountancy firm [[UHY Hacker Young]] as administrators. This automatically incurred a nine-point penalty from the Premier League which came into effect on 17 March and consigned the team to almost certain relegation, which was mathematically confirmed on 10 April 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/apr/10/portsmouth-relegated-premier-league | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Paolo | last=Bandini | title=Portsmouth relegated from top flight after West Ham beat Sunderland | date=10 April 2010}}</ref> On 9 April 2010, it was announced David Lampitt would be joining Portsmouth as their new CEO after he had worked a period of notice at the FA, his current employer.\n\nPortsmouth were relegated to the [[EFL Championship]] (the new Tier 2 level name) the following day on 10 April 2010 after West Ham won.  Portsmouth won their FA Cup semi-final match against Tottenham 2\u20130 after extra-time the next day, with goals from [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Piquionne]] and [[Kevin-Prince Boateng]] winning the match. They faced Chelsea in the [[2010 FA Cup Final|final]] at Wembley on 15 May 2010 and lost 1\u20130 to a goal from [[Didier Drogba]]. Despite being the FA Cup finalists, the club were denied a licence to play European football the following season in the [[UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8558580.stm |publisher=BBC Sport | title=Portsmouth Europa League appeal rejected by FA | date=22 April 2010 | accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> In May, Grant resigned as Portsmouth manager. On 17 June, the club's creditors voted for a [[Trading while insolvent (UK)#Company Voluntary Arrangement (CVA)|company voluntary arrangement]] (CVA), with an 81.3% majority;<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/17/portsmouth-exit-administration-cva | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Jamie | last=Jackson | title=Portsmouth to exit administration after agreeing CVA | date=17 June 2010}}</ref> HMRC, Paul Hart and the agent of Portsmouth midfielder [[Tommy Smith (footballer, born 1980)|Tommy Smith]] were the only ones to reject it, but HMRC appealed against the CVA due to the reduction of its considerable debt.<ref>{{cite news|last=Slater |first=Matt |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8746162.stm |title=Football \u2013 Portsmouth creditors vote in favour of deal over debts |publisher=BBC News |date=17 June 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> On 15 July 2010, HMRC appealed against the proposed CVA on the last day before it would be formally agreed,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8826344.stm |publisher=BBC Sport | title=Portsmouth suffer fresh setback after HMRC appeal | date=19 July 2010 | accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref> the case was originally going to take place in October 2010, but after an appeal from the administrators at the club it was set for 3 August at the High Court in London. The case was heard by Mr Justice Mann from 3 to 5 August where, having heard submissions from both sides, he turned down HMRC's appeal on all five counts it had put forward. HMRC decided not to appeal against the verdict, leaving Portsmouth's administrators to formally agree the CVA and bring the club out of administration.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Slater |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/mattslater/2010/08/pompey_1_hmrc_0.html |title=Matt Slater: Pompey snatch last-gasp victory over taxman |publisher=BBC |date=6 August 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> On 17 August, Balram Chainrai completed his takeover of the club and passed the owners' and directors' [[fit and proper person test]].\n\n===2010\u20132017: Decline and relegation to League Two===\nFormer [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] manager [[Steve Cotterill]] was appointed manager of relegated Portsmouth in the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] June 2010 on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8747461.stm |title=Football \u2013 Portsmouth appoint Steve Cotterill as manager |publisher=BBC News |date=18 June 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> On 22 October, Portsmouth issued a statement saying, \"It appears likely that the club will now be closed down and liquidated by the administrators,\"<ref name=CloseDown>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/9120108.stm |title=Football \u2013 Portsmouth 'likely to close down' |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 October 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> but key creditor Alexandre Gaydamak announced the next day that he had reached an agreement which could save their future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11688_6465066,00.html |title=Pompey future secured &#124; Championship  |publisher=Sky Sports |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> It was revealed just hours later that Portsmouth had finally come out of administration, with Balram Chainrai regaining control of the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/portsmouth/8083715/Portsmouth-out-of-administration-after-deal-reached-with-Alexandre-Gaydamak.html|title=Portsmouth out of administration after deal reached with Alexandre Gaydamak|date=24 October 2010|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> On 1 June 2011, Convers Sports Initiatives (CSI) owned by Russian [[Vladimir Aleksandrovich Antonov|Vladimir Antonov]] completed its takeover of the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/13614706.stm|title=Convers Sports Initiatives complete Portsmouth takeover |date=1 June 2011|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 October 2011, Steve Cotterill agreed a compensation package to be allowed to take the vacant [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] manager's position.<ref>{{cite news|author=Neil Moxley |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2049169/Steve-Cotterill-takes-Nottingham-Forest.html |title=Cotterill leaves Pompey to take the reins at Forest on deal until 2015 |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=14 October 2011 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> He was succeeded by [[Michael Appleton]], who was announced as the new manager on 10 November 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15616925.stm|title=Portsmouth name Michael Appleton as new manager |date=10 November 2011|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref> On 23 November 2011, a Europe-wide arrest warrant was issued for Portsmouth owner Vladimir Antonov by Lithuanian prosecutors as part of an investigation into alleged [[asset stripping]] at Lithuanian bank [[Bankas Snoras]], which was 68% owned by Antonov and had gone into temporary administration the previous week. Operations in another of Antonov's banks, [[Latvijas Krajbanka]], were suspended by Latvian authorities for similar reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-15859800|title=Arrest Warrant for Portsmouth FC Owner Vladimir Antonov |date=23 November 2011|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref> Antonov was subsequently arrested at his offices in London on 24 November and was bailed.<ref name=\"bailed\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-15887821|title=Pompey owner Vladimir Antonov bailed in Snoras Bank asset-stripping case|date=25 November 2011|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> He shortly afterwards resigned as chairman of Portsmouth after parent company CSI entered administration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15944523.stm|title=Portsmouth owner Vladimir Antonov steps down|date=29 November 2011|publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref> On 24 January 2012, Portsmouth were issued with a winding up petition by HMRC for over \u00a31.6&nbsp;million in unpaid taxes, which was heard on 20 February.<ref>{{cite news|title=Portsmouth Football Club Statement |url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/LatestNews/news/Portsmouth-Football-Club-Statement-3049.aspx |publisher=Portsmouth F.C. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111045303/http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/LatestNews/news/Portsmouth-Football-Club-Statement-3049.aspx |archivedate=11 November 2012 }}</ref> On 17 February 2012, Portsmouth went into administration for the second time in two years, bringing them an automatic 10-point deduction.<ref>{{cite news|title=Championship \u2013 Portsmouth in administration, docked 10 points|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/17022012/58/championship-portsmouth-administration.html|publisher=Yahoo! Eurosport|date=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16943651|title=Portsmouth Football Club back in administration|date=17 February 2012|publisher= BBC Sport |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> Administrator [[Trevor Birch]] admitted that the financial situation was \"worse than we first feared\" and that Portsmouth were \"struggling to make the end of the season\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Portsmouth may not have enough money to finish season|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17137954|publisher= BBC Sport|date=23 February 2012}}</ref> On 11 April 2012, reports from administrators PKF revealed that Portsmouth owed \u00a358&nbsp;million with \u00a338&nbsp;million being owed to UHY Hacker Young, \u00a310.5&nbsp;million investment made by Vladimir Antonov's CSI remained outstanding, players were due \u00a33.5&nbsp;million in wages and bonuses for the last two seasons, while \u00a32.3&nbsp;million was owed to HMRC and, additionally, \u00a33.7&nbsp;million was owed for general trade.<ref>{{cite news|title=Portsmouth administrators' report reveals \u00a358&nbsp;million. debt|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17679909|date=11 April 2012|accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref> On 21 April, Portsmouth were relegated from the Championship after a 2\u20131 loss to [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], the first time in 30 years that the club had played at that level.\n\nFollowing Pompey's relegation to [[Football League One|League One]], the entire professional playing squad left the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawrence to leave Pompey |url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/LatestNews/news/Lawrence-To-Leave-Pompey-3585.aspx |publisher=Portsmouth Football Club |date=10 August 2012 |accessdate=10 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812024525/http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/LatestNews/news/Lawrence-To-Leave-Pompey-3585.aspx |archivedate=12 August 2012 }}</ref> The team were given a 10-point deduction in December 2012 for their financial problems.<ref>{{cite news|title=Portsmouth: Football League reaffirm points deduction|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20669252|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 December 2012|accessdate=29 December 2012}}</ref> On 7 November 2012, it was announced that Michael Appleton had left Portsmouth to become the manager of [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20236445|title=Michael Appleton: Blackpool name Portsmouth manager as new boss|date=7 November 2012|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref> On 9 November 2012, Chanrai halted his attempt to buy the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20268344|title=Portsmouth: Balram Chainrai suspends bid for club|date=9 November 2012|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref> Six days later, the Pompey Supporters Trust signed a conditional agreement with PFK to buy the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Portsmouth set to be sold to Pompey Supporters' Trust|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20338754|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 November 2012|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> Portsmouth were unable to find a manager on a long-term basis due to their financial state. The club went on a record winless run of 23 matches, finally ending on 2 March 2013 as Portsmouth won 2\u20131 away at [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556921|title=Crewe 1 \u2013 2 Portsmouth|date=2 March 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> On 10 April 2013, a deal with administrators was reached,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22098749|title=Portsmouth: Supporters poised for takeover|date=10 April 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref> although the Pompey Supporters' Trust had not yet finalised the purchase.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-22097965|title=Tears as Portsmouth fans reclaim football club|date=10 April 2013|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref> Portsmouth were relegated (for the second successive season) to League Two at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22075591|title=Matt Smith's header ensured Lee Johnson's Oldham beat father Gary's Yeovil and condemned both Hartlepool and Portsmouth to relegation|date=16 April 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> On 19 April 2013, Portsmouth exited administration when the [[Pompey Supporters Trust|Pompey Supporters' Trust]] (PST) deal to buy the club was completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22167294|title=Portsmouth come out of administration|date=19 April 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref> Former caretaker Guy Whittingham was appointed manager on a permanent basis with a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/24/portsmouth-appoint-guy-whittingham-manager | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Portsmouth name Guy Whittingham as permanent manager | date=24 April 2013 |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> Portsmouth sold over 10,000 season tickets for the [[2013\u201314 Portsmouth F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]], a record for any League Two club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/sport/pompey/pompey-season-ticket-sales-top-10-000-1-5283675 |title=Pompey season ticket sales top 10,000 |publisher=Portsmouth News |date=14 July 2013 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Whittingham was sacked and a month later ex-[[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]] manager [[Richie Barker (footballer, born 1975)|Richie Barker]] was appointed Portsmouth boss, along with [[Steve Coppell]] as the director of football. Barker was sacked after 20 games in charge, with the club in serious danger of relegation to the [[Football Conference]], and [[Andy Awford]] was again made caretaker manager.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26765666 | title = Richie Barker sacked as Portsmouth manager| date= 27 March 2014 | accessdate = 27 March 2014 |publisher = BBC Sport}}</ref> He won five games out of five played, guaranteeing Pompey's survival in League Two.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/sport/pompey/pompey-celebrate-in-style-1-6013083 |title=Pompey Celebrate in Style |date=21 April 2014 |accessdate=21 April 2014 |publisher=Portsmouth News}}</ref> On 1 May 2014, Awford was appointed Pompey's permanent manager, signing a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/article/awford-appointed-pompey-manager-1520647.aspx |title=Awford appointed Pompey manager |publisher=Portsmouth Football Club |date=1 May 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn a historic announcement on 29 September 2014, the club was able to declare itself debt-free after paying back all creditors and legacy payments to ex-players.<ref>{{cite web|title=Portsmouth now debt-free following Supporters Trust takeover|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29408776|publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 September 2014 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> The news came 18 months after the PST took control of the club. Following an unsuccessful [[2014\u201315 Portsmouth F.C. season|EFL League Two 2014\u201315 campaign]], [[Paul Cook (footballer)|Paul Cook]] was appointed new manager of Portsmouth on 12 May 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32702867|title=Paul Cook: Portsmouth appoint Chesterfield boss as manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 May 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nPaul Cook led Portsmouth to an EFL League Two play-off spot in the [[2015\u201316 Football League Two|2015\u201316 season]] after a 2\u20130 away win at [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] on 30 April 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/article/hartlepool-united-0-pompey-2-at-victoria-park-in-sky-bet-league-2-3087122.aspx|title=Hartlepool United 0 Pompey 2 |publisher=Portsmouth Football Club|first=Neil |last=Weld |date=30 April 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> but lost to [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] in the semi-final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36240107|title=Plymouth Argyle 1\u20130 Portsmouth (agg 3\u20132)|author=Brent Pilnick|publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 May 2016 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016\u201317 EFL League Two|2016\u201317 season]], Paul Cook's side secured promotion to League One with a 3\u20131 win away at Notts County on 17 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39550094 |title=Notts County 1 \u2013 3 Portsmouth |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 April 2017 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> On 6 May, the final match of the season, Portsmouth topped the table (for the first time in the season) following the 6\u20131 home win against Cheltenham and were crowned champions of League Two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/39784039|title=League Two: Pools relegated, Pompey champions as it happened |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 May 2017}}</ref> Paul Cook resigned on 31 May 2017 to join [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2017/may/cook-leaves-pompey//|title=Cook Leaves Pompey |publisher=Portsmouth Football Club|date=31 May 2017 |accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> [[Kenny Jackett]] was appointed the new manager on Friday 2 June 2017. In May the Pompey Supporters' Trust (PST) voted in favour<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pompeytrust.com/news/pst-shareholders-vote-to-sell-to-tornante|title=PST Shareholders vote to sell to 'Tornante' |date=22 May 2017 |accessdate=6 July 2018|publisher=Pompy Supports Trust}}</ref> of a proposed bid by [[The Tornante Company]], headed by former Disney chief executive [[Michael Eisner]], to take over the club which was completed on 3 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40000639|title=Portsmouth: Supporters' Trust approves Michael Eisner's takeover proposal|publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 May 2017 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11674/10888875/portsmouth-supporters-trust-approve-michael-eisners-proposed-takeover|title=Pompey Trust accept Eisner bid|publisher=Sky Sports |date=22 May 2017 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"portsmouthfc.co\" />\n\n===2017\u2013present: League One===\nPortsmouth began the [[2017\u201318 Portsmouth F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]] in [[EFL League One|League One]], following their [[EFL League Two|League Two]] championship win in the previous [[2016\u201317 Portsmouth F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]]. On 15 March 2018, Portsmouth revealed a newly redesigned club crest, featuring a new nautical compass star and an \"1898\" date, added for the founding year of the football club. The new crest was introduced for the new 2018\u201319 season.<ref name=\"portsmouthfc.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2018/march/pompey-unveil-new-crest/ |title=Pompey Unveil New Crest |publisher=Portsmouth F.C. |date=15 March 2018 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> Portsmouth ended the [[2017\u201318 EFL League One|2017\u201318 League One season]] in 8th position on 66 points, missing the play-off places by 5 points.\n\nThe [[2018\u201319 EFL League One]] season began in August with a run of four consecutive league wins and their best league start since 1980\u201381.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/portsmouth/tab/matches/season/1981/ |title=Portsmouth football club match record: 1981 |work=11v11.com |accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref> Portsmouth remained undefeated in the 2018\u201319 EFL League One campaign for eleven consecutive league matches and topped the League One table, before being defeated by [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in the twelfth match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/portsmouth/tab/matches/ |title=Portsmouth football club complete match record |work=11v11.com |accessdate=26 October 2018 }}</ref> On Sunday 31 March 2019, Portsmouth met [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in the [[2019 EFL Trophy Final]] at Wembley Stadium. The match finished 1\u20131 after normal time, and 2\u20132 after 30 minutes of extra time. A penalty shootout followed, with Portsmouth winning 5\u20134.<ref name=2019trophy>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47709134 |title=Checkatrade Trophy final |work=BBC Sport |author=Adam Williams |date=31 March 2019 |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> Portsmouth's regular EFL League One season concluded on 4 May 2019, with the team finishing 4th and qualifying for the League One play-offs. In the play-off semi-finals, Portsmouth were met by fifth placed Sunderland. The first leg match at the [[Stadium of Light]] on 11 May 2019 was won 1-0 by Sunderland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48165374|title=Sunderland 1-0 Portsmouth: Chris Maguire gives Black Cats' 10 men win|date=11 May 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The second leg was played at Fratton Park on 16 May 2019 and ended 0-0, which meant Portsmouth lost 0-1 overall and missed a Wembley play-off final for promotion to The Championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48210117|title=Portsmouth 0-0 Sunderland (0-1 agg): Black Cats reach League One play-off final|date=16 May 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> \n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 Portsmouth F.C. season|2019\u201320 season]], Portsmouth achieved a winning run of nine consecutive matches in all competitions, setting a new win record for the club since Portsmouth joined the Football League in 1920.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2020/february/match-report-for-tranmere-rovers-vs-portsmouth-on-08-feb-20/|title=Tranmere 0 Pompey 2|website=www.portsmouthfc.co.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The record run of nine matches began with an FA Cup Third Round win on Saturday 4th January 2020 away at [[Fleetwood Town]], with the record-setting ninth game played away at [[Tranmere Rovers]] on Saturday 8 February 2020 in an EFL League One match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/matches/results/|title=Matches - Portsmouth|website=www.portsmouthfc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> On 18 February 2020, Portsmouth qualified for the [[2020 EFL Trophy Final]] after narrowly defeating [[Exeter City]] 3-2 in the semi-final at Fratton Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2020/february/match-report-for-portsmouth-vs-exeter-city-on-18-feb-20/|title=Pompey 3 Exeter 2|website=www.portsmouthfc.co.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> Portsmouth will return to Wembley Stadium to defend the EFL Trophy as champions on Sunday 5 April 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2019/june/key-dates-announced-ahead-of-201920-season/|title=Key dates announced ahead of 2019/20 season|website=www.efl.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> - coincidentally, the 122nd anniversary of the founding of Portsmouth FC in 1898. Their opponents will be [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]], and will be the first ever meeting between the two clubs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Pompey/status/1230251680480006144|title=#Pompey's first ever meeting with @SalfordCityFC will take place at @wembleystadium in the @LeasingcomTrphy final on Sunday, April 5|last=FC|first=Portsmouth|date=2020-02-19|website=@Pompey|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> On Friday 13 March 2020, all professional football in England was suspended until (at least) 30 April due to the global [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 coronavirus]] pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SkySportsNews/status/1240628952747642880|title=The FA, Premier League and EFL statement confirms they have extended the season \"indefinitely\" to ensure it is completed. Rules had stated the domestic season should be finished by June 1|last=News|first=Sky Sports|date=2020-03-19|website=@SkySportsNews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Players==\n===Current squad===\n{{updated|12 March 2020}}<ref name=\"Team\">{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/team/ |title=First Team Squad |publisher=Portsmouth Football Club |accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{football squad start}}\n{{football squad player|nat=SCO|pos=GK|name=[[Craig MacGillivray (footballer)|Craig MacGillivray]]|other=|no=1}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Lee Brown (footballer)|Lee Brown]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|vice-captain]]|no=3}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Tom Naylor]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]]|no=4}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Paul Downing (footballer)|Paul Downing]]|other=|no=5}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Christian Burgess]]|other=|no=6}}\n{{football squad player|nat=AUS|pos=MF|name=[[Ryan Williams (footballer, born 1993)|Ryan Williams]]|other=|no=7}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Brett Pitman]]|other=|no=8}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Oliver Hawkins]]|other=|no=9}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[John Marquis]]|other=|no=10}}\n{{football squad player|nat=IRL|pos=MF|name=[[Ronan Curtis]]|other=|no=11}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[James Bolton (footballer)|James Bolton]]|other=|no=13}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Andy Cannon]]|other=|no=14}}\n{{football squad player|nat=SCO|pos=MF|name=[[Ross McCrorie]]|other=on loan from [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]|no=15}}\n{{football squad mid}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Jack Whatmough]]|other=|no=16}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Bryn Morris]]|other=|no=17}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Reeco Hackett-Fairchild]]|other=|no=18}}                                              \n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Marcus Harness]]|other=|no=19}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Sean Raggett]]|other=on loan from [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]]|no=20}}\n{{football squad player|nat=WAL|pos=FW|name=[[Ellis Harrison]]|other=|no=22}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Cameron McGeehan]]|other=on loan from [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]|no=24}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Gareth Evans (footballer, born 1988)|Gareth Evans]]|other=|no=26}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Ben Close]]|other=|no=33}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=[[Alex Bass]]|other=|no=35}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Brandon Haunstrup]]|other=|no=38}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Steve Seddon]]|other=on loan from [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]|no=42}}\n{{football squad player|nat=USA|pos=GK|name=Duncan Turnbull|other=|no=\u2014}}\n\n{{football squad end}}\n\n===Out on loan===\n{{football squad start}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=[[Luke McGee]]|other=on loan at [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]]                                                   |no=21}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Adam May (footballer)|Adam May]]|other=on loan at [[Boreham Wood F.C.|Boreham Wood]]                                 |no=30}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Matthew Casey (footballer)|Matt Casey]]|other=on loan at [[Bognor Regis Town F.C.|Bognor Regis Town]]                |no=31}}\n\n{{football squad end}}\n\n===Reserves and Academy===\n{{main|Portsmouth F.C. Reserves and Academy}}\n{{football squad start}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Joe Hancott]]|no=25}}\n{{football squad player|nat=NIR|pos=FW|name=Eoin Teggart                                         |no=36}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Haji Mnoga]]                                       |no=37}}\n{{football squad player|nat=WAL|pos=DF|name=Harvey Rew                                           |no=39}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=Leon Pitman                                          |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Tom Bruce                                            |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Liam Kelly                                           |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Charlie Bell                                         |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad mid}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Stan Bridgman                                        |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Harrison Brook                                       |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Ethan Robb                                           |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=NIR|pos=MF|name=Gerard Storey                                        |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=NIR|pos=FW|name=Harry Anderson                                       |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=KOR|pos=FW|name=Seok Jae Lee                                          |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=Alfie Stanley                                        |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad end}}\n\n===Out on loan===\n{{football squad start}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Bradley Lethbridge]]|other=on loan at [[Bognor Regis Town F.C.|Bognor Regis Town]]                               |no=40}}\n{{football squad player|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Harry Kavanagh|other=on loan at [[Bognor Regis Town F.C.|Bognor Regis Town]]                                       |no=\u2014}}\n{{football squad end}}\n\n===Notable players===\nFor a list of notable players and players who played for Portsmouth for more than 100 games in a sortable-list format, see ''[[List of Portsmouth F.C. players]]''.\n\n===Retired and reserved numbers===\n* Number '''1''' was temporarily retired for the 2001\u201302 season in respect to goalkeeper [[Aaron Flahavan]], who died in a car crash in August 2001, days after being handed the squad number 1 for the first time. Since the 2003\u201304 season, number '''13''' shirt was reserved in respect for him, as this was the number he wore for the majority of his stay at the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portsmouth.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=165298|title=There's only one No.13|work=VitalFootball.co.uk |author=Chix |date=10 August 2009 |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> Ten years after his death, however, the number 13 was again used, first by [[Stephen Henderson (footballer, born 1988)|Stephen Henderson]], then by [[Simon Eastwood]], [[Johannes Ertl|Johnny Ertl]] and [[James Bolton (footballer)|James Bolton]] respectively.\n* Number '''12''' is reserved for the [[Fan (person)|fans]] (often referred to as the 12th man).{{citation needed|date=October 2010}}\n* Number '''58''' is \"Nelson\" the club mascot's number.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/pompeynelson?lang=en |title=Nelson/58 |work=twitter.com |accessdate=18 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Portsmouth Player of the Season (since 1968)===\nSource:?{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n* 